WEBVTT

1
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
<font color=#0080C0><b>*** Subtitles by dylux ***</b></font>

2
00:01:05.398 --> 00:01:07.524
BENJAMIN: <i>l have long feared</i>

3
00:01:08.401 --> 00:01:11.945
<i>that my sins would return</i>
<i>to visit me.</i>

4
00:01:13.281 --> 00:01:16.033
<i>And the cost is more</i>
<i>than I can bear.</i>

5
00:01:32.926 --> 00:01:35.094
<i>(HOOVES CLOMPING)</i>

6
00:01:44.020 --> 00:01:46.105
Samuel! A postrider!

7
00:01:51.069 --> 00:01:53.612
<i>(CHILDREN LAUGHING)</i>

8
00:01:57.200 --> 00:01:58.242
An "R."

9
00:01:58.451 --> 00:01:59.618
Good.

10
00:02:01.454 --> 00:02:02.663
What about this one?

11
00:02:41.161 --> 00:02:43.078
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

12
00:03:25.538 --> 00:03:28.040
Father! Father!

13
00:03:29.417 --> 00:03:33.378
BENJAMIN: Nine pounds, eleven ounces.
That's perfect. Perfect.

14
00:03:33.922 --> 00:03:35.881
Father, a postrider!

15
00:03:36.591 --> 00:03:38.175
Did you finish planting
the south field?

16
00:03:38.551 --> 00:03:39.593
More than half.

17
00:03:39.802 --> 00:03:43.138
Those swimming breaks really cut
into the day, don't they?

18
00:03:45.350 --> 00:03:46.725
Told you.

19
00:03:57.153 --> 00:03:58.445
GABRIEL: Thomas.

20
00:03:58.696 --> 00:04:00.155
Wait for Father.

21
00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:02.658
<i>(SIGHS)</i>

22
00:04:18.883 --> 00:04:20.634
<i>(CREAKS)</i>

23
00:04:36.234 --> 00:04:37.359
<i>(CRACKS)</i>

24
00:04:45.576 --> 00:04:47.494
<i>(GRUNTS)</i>

25
00:05:00.049 --> 00:05:01.091
Sorry.

26
00:05:33.416 --> 00:05:37.127
MARGARET: That's her. The North Star.

27
00:05:38.296 --> 00:05:39.504
See?

28
00:05:39.839 --> 00:05:43.133
You start from the front two stars
of the Big Dipper.

29
00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:45.177
And then you count up.

30
00:05:45.470 --> 00:05:48.680
You count up five finger lengths

31
00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:51.641
and it's right there.

32
00:05:52.894 --> 00:05:55.729
And she'll always be
looking down on us.

33
00:05:56.064 --> 00:05:59.191
And protect us. Forever.

34
00:06:01.194 --> 00:06:02.736
Come. Into bed.

35
00:06:10.411 --> 00:06:12.829
Good night. Good night, Meg.

36
00:06:14.499 --> 00:06:17.250
It helps her to know Mother's there.

37
00:06:21.839 --> 00:06:22.923
Good night.

38
00:06:36.229 --> 00:06:38.814
<i>(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)</i>

39
00:06:54.205 --> 00:06:55.664
<i>(CLINKING)</i>

40
00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:01.044
<i>(EXHALES SHARPLY)</i>

41
00:07:04.924 --> 00:07:06.883
So what was in the mail?

42
00:07:18.646 --> 00:07:21.106
"The New York and
Pennsylvania assemblies

43
00:07:21.274 --> 00:07:23.608
are debating independence."

44
00:07:23.776 --> 00:07:26.361
What about the middle colonies?

45
00:07:28.948 --> 00:07:31.283
"In Chestertown,
they burned the customs house

46
00:07:31.451 --> 00:07:33.952
and tar and feathered
two magistrates.

47
00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:36.455
They died of-- They died of burns."

48
00:07:36.622 --> 00:07:38.707
Damn fools.

49
00:07:38.875 --> 00:07:41.168
Who? The writers or the magistrates?

50
00:07:41.335 --> 00:07:44.629
Uh, what does it say about
the Continental Congress?

51
00:07:48.551 --> 00:07:53.138
It says here they'll make
a declaration of independence by July.

52
00:08:01.439 --> 00:08:02.939
<i>(MOUTHING)</i>

53
00:08:10.531 --> 00:08:12.574
Peter Cuppin
joined the Continentals.

54
00:08:19.081 --> 00:08:21.416
He's 17, a year younger than I.

55
00:08:27.965 --> 00:08:29.174
<i>(EXHALES SHARPLY)</i>

56
00:08:32.136 --> 00:08:36.181
Well, the assembly's been convened,
so I've been called to Charles Town.

57
00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:38.558
We're going to Charles Town?
We are.

58
00:08:38.768 --> 00:08:40.060
We leave in the morning.

59
00:08:56.953 --> 00:08:58.578
Yah. Yah.

60
00:08:58.829 --> 00:09:03.250
<i>(PEOPLE SHOUTING AND CHATTERING)</i>

61
00:09:22.853 --> 00:09:24.187
Charlotte.

62
00:09:24.355 --> 00:09:26.481
The children are here.

63
00:09:29.485 --> 00:09:31.611
Thank you.

64
00:09:33.656 --> 00:09:36.074
<i>(GIGGLING)</i>

65
00:09:36.325 --> 00:09:38.827
CHILDREN: Aunt Charlotte!
Aunt Charlotte!

66
00:09:38.995 --> 00:09:40.829
Margaret, William, look at you.

67
00:09:41.831 --> 00:09:43.331
WILLIAM: Missed you.

68
00:09:44.166 --> 00:09:46.751
They're huge.
What have you been feeding them?

69
00:09:47.545 --> 00:09:51.047
Well, they're from good stock.
On their mother's side, of course.

70
00:09:52.091 --> 00:09:55.677
Thank you. Come inside.
Wait until you see what I have.

71
00:09:55.886 --> 00:09:57.137
CHILDREN: Presents? Presents for us?

72
00:09:57.305 --> 00:09:58.346
Move slowly.

73
00:09:58.556 --> 00:10:00.890
You two, keep an eye
on these heathens, will you?

74
00:10:01.058 --> 00:10:02.475
- Hey, Thomas!
- Oh!

75
00:10:03.227 --> 00:10:04.561
- Oh.
- Sorry.

76
00:10:12.695 --> 00:10:16.740
I have this for you, Susan.
It belonged to your mother.

77
00:10:22.913 --> 00:10:24.998
She's still not talking?

78
00:10:26.459 --> 00:10:27.792
No.

79
00:10:30.713 --> 00:10:32.547
It does me good to see you.

80
00:10:34.091 --> 00:10:37.719
<i>(CROWD ROARING)</i>

81
00:10:41.974 --> 00:10:46.686
<i>(FLUTE PLAYS "YANKEE DOODLE")</i>

82
00:10:49.023 --> 00:10:50.440
Look, there's Gabriel.

83
00:10:50.608 --> 00:10:52.776
THOMAS: Gabriel.

84
00:10:58.240 --> 00:10:59.866
MAN 1: Hang King George!

85
00:11:07.917 --> 00:11:10.085
Harry Burwell is here recruiting.

86
00:11:10.753 --> 00:11:13.213
The governor has vowed if the
assembly votes a single shilling

87
00:11:13.422 --> 00:11:16.257
to the Continental Army,
he'll dissolve the body.

88
00:11:18.135 --> 00:11:22.889
Wouldn't that force our delegates in Philadelphia
to vote for independence?

89
00:11:23.057 --> 00:11:24.891
Yes.

90
00:11:25.518 --> 00:11:29.104
Send us off to war
alongside Massachusetts.

91
00:11:31.190 --> 00:11:34.234
MAN 1: Get King George!

92
00:11:34.860 --> 00:11:37.987
- MAN 2: Hang them all!
- MAN 1: Hang the lot of them!

93
00:11:39.448 --> 00:11:41.533
That's enough.
Very well, children, inside.

94
00:11:41.701 --> 00:11:45.078
Come along now. Inside now.

95
00:11:54.588 --> 00:11:57.132
Burwell will be counting on
your vote.

96
00:11:57.299 --> 00:12:00.719
And he'll expect you
to be the first to enlist.

97
00:12:00.886 --> 00:12:02.303
Yes, I imagine so.

98
00:12:02.471 --> 00:12:04.305
<i>(GLASS SHATTERS)</i>

99
00:12:05.433 --> 00:12:09.227
I'm sorry, the heathens are...

100
00:12:10.938 --> 00:12:13.189
They have long needed
a woman in their lives.

101
00:12:14.275 --> 00:12:15.692
A mother.

102
00:12:15.860 --> 00:12:18.153
Especially Susan.

103
00:12:26.954 --> 00:12:28.955
<i>(MEN CHATTERING)</i>

104
00:12:29.832 --> 00:12:32.041
My name is Peter Howard.

105
00:12:32.626 --> 00:12:36.129
I lost most of my hearing
and my left leg

106
00:12:36.589 --> 00:12:40.008
fighting for the Crown
in the French and Indian War.

107
00:12:40.718 --> 00:12:43.428
And how did King George reward me?

108
00:12:43.721 --> 00:12:46.431
He cuts off my other leg
with his taxes.

109
00:12:46.599 --> 00:12:47.807
<i>(CLEARS THROAT)</i>

110
00:12:47.975 --> 00:12:49.768
Miss Howard, isn't it?

111
00:12:50.936 --> 00:12:52.937
You know who I am, Gabriel Martin.

112
00:12:54.398 --> 00:12:58.443
The last time you saw me,
I was 1 1 and you put ink in my tea.

113
00:12:59.320 --> 00:13:03.573
Oh, I believe that was one of my younger brothers.
Perhaps Samuel or Nathan.

114
00:13:04.074 --> 00:13:08.203
It was you, and it turned
my teeth black for a month.

115
00:13:08.579 --> 00:13:10.580
I, uh...

116
00:13:10.748 --> 00:13:15.543
PETER: --and send a message to King George
he will never forget!

117
00:13:17.838 --> 00:13:19.214
Our first order of business--

118
00:13:19.465 --> 00:13:21.341
And our last, if we vote a levy!

119
00:13:21.842 --> 00:13:22.967
JUDGE: Order, order!

120
00:13:23.177 --> 00:13:25.220
Mr. Simms, you do not have the floor.

121
00:13:25.513 --> 00:13:29.599
Our first order of business will be, an address
by Colonel Harry Burwell of the Continental Army.

122
00:13:29.809 --> 00:13:31.184
Colonel Burwell.

123
00:13:35.022 --> 00:13:37.148
BURWELL: You all know why I'm here.

124
00:13:37.775 --> 00:13:39.442
I'm not an orator.

125
00:13:40.152 --> 00:13:44.364
And I would not try to convince you
of the worthiness of our cause.

126
00:13:45.699 --> 00:13:47.242
I'm a soldier.

127
00:13:48.035 --> 00:13:50.245
And we are at war.

128
00:13:50.871 --> 00:13:54.415
From Philadelphia, we expect
a declaration of independence.

129
00:13:55.209 --> 00:13:57.669
Eight of the 13 colonies have
levied money

130
00:13:57.878 --> 00:14:00.004
in support of a continental army.

131
00:14:00.464 --> 00:14:02.841
I ask that South Carolina
be the ninth.

132
00:14:03.384 --> 00:14:06.594
Massachusetts and Virginia
may be at war,

133
00:14:06.846 --> 00:14:08.972
but South Carolina is not!

134
00:14:09.181 --> 00:14:10.223
Hear, hear.

135
00:14:10.516 --> 00:14:14.561
This is not a war for the independence
of one or two colonies,

136
00:14:14.895 --> 00:14:17.146
but for the independence
of one nation.

137
00:14:17.356 --> 00:14:19.399
And what nation is that?

138
00:14:19.608 --> 00:14:21.818
An American nation!

139
00:14:22.027 --> 00:14:24.654
There is no such nation
and to speak of one is treason.

140
00:14:24.864 --> 00:14:27.782
We are citizens
of an American nation.

141
00:14:27.992 --> 00:14:30.618
And our rights are being threatened

142
00:14:30.828 --> 00:14:33.413
by a tyrant 3000 miles away.

143
00:14:33.664 --> 00:14:36.124
Would you tell me, please,
Mr. Howard,

144
00:14:36.333 --> 00:14:40.211
why should I trade one tyrant
3000 miles away

145
00:14:40.421 --> 00:14:43.298
for 3000 tyrants one mile away?

146
00:14:43.966 --> 00:14:45.341
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

147
00:14:48.262 --> 00:14:52.599
An elected legislature can trample
a man's rights as easily as a king can.

148
00:14:53.934 --> 00:14:55.143
BURWELL: Captain Martin,

149
00:14:56.645 --> 00:14:58.354
I understood you to be a patriot.

150
00:14:58.898 --> 00:15:02.483
If you mean by "patriot," am I angry
about taxation without representation?

151
00:15:02.651 --> 00:15:03.985
Well, yes, I am.

152
00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:09.407
Should the American colonies
govern themselves independently?

153
00:15:09.742 --> 00:15:12.577
I believe they can. And they should.

154
00:15:13.412 --> 00:15:17.040
But if you're asking me am I willing
to go to war with England,

155
00:15:17.249 --> 00:15:19.876
well, then the answer is
most definitely no.

156
00:15:20.044 --> 00:15:22.712
<i>(CHATTERING)</i>

157
00:15:24.340 --> 00:15:28.593
This from the same Captain Benjamin Martin
whose fury was so famous

158
00:15:29.011 --> 00:15:30.929
during the Wilderness campaign?

159
00:15:32.306 --> 00:15:34.140
I was intemperate in my youth.

160
00:15:34.350 --> 00:15:36.225
Temperance can be
a convenient disguise for fear.

161
00:15:37.019 --> 00:15:39.896
Mr. Middleton, I fought
with Captain Martin

162
00:15:40.105 --> 00:15:42.857
under Washington
in the French and Indian War.

163
00:15:43.484 --> 00:15:45.068
There's not a man in this room

164
00:15:45.277 --> 00:15:48.696
or anywhere for that matter, to whom
I would more willingly trust my life.

165
00:15:48.864 --> 00:15:49.906
MEN: Hear, hear.

166
00:15:50.491 --> 00:15:52.700
There are alternatives to war.

167
00:15:53.994 --> 00:15:55.954
We take our case before the king.

168
00:15:56.163 --> 00:15:57.622
We plead with him.
Yes, we tried that.

169
00:15:57.831 --> 00:16:00.541
Well, then, we try again and again
if necessary to avoid a war.

170
00:16:00.709 --> 00:16:04.379
Benjamin, I was at Bunker Hill.

171
00:16:05.214 --> 00:16:07.298
The British advanced three times.

172
00:16:07.549 --> 00:16:11.552
We killed over 700 of them at point-blank range
and still they took the ground.

173
00:16:12.054 --> 00:16:14.847
That is the measure of their resolve.

174
00:16:15.849 --> 00:16:18.184
If your principles dictate independence,

175
00:16:18.394 --> 00:16:20.687
then war is the only way.

176
00:16:21.188 --> 00:16:22.230
It is come to that.

177
00:16:22.398 --> 00:16:24.482
MEN: Hear, hear.

178
00:16:26.694 --> 00:16:28.528
I have seven children.

179
00:16:29.238 --> 00:16:30.822
My wife is dead.

180
00:16:32.574 --> 00:16:34.826
Now, who's to care for them
if I go to war?

181
00:16:37.329 --> 00:16:40.623
Wars are not fought
only by childless men.

182
00:16:41.208 --> 00:16:42.500
Granted.

183
00:16:45.379 --> 00:16:47.338
But mark my words.

184
00:16:49.675 --> 00:16:53.511
This war will be fought,
not on the frontier,

185
00:16:53.721 --> 00:16:56.514
or on some distant battlefield,

186
00:16:57.558 --> 00:16:59.183
but amongst us.

187
00:16:59.393 --> 00:17:01.352
Among our homes.

188
00:17:02.479 --> 00:17:05.523
Our children will learn of it
with their own eyes.

189
00:17:08.569 --> 00:17:11.404
And the innocent will die
with the rest of us.

190
00:17:15.409 --> 00:17:16.993
I will not fight.

191
00:17:18.037 --> 00:17:20.830
And because I will not fight,
I will not cast a vote

192
00:17:21.040 --> 00:17:23.791
that will send others to fight
in my stead.

193
00:17:26.128 --> 00:17:28.004
And your principles?

194
00:17:31.550 --> 00:17:34.761
I'm a parent. I haven't got
the luxury of principles.

195
00:17:43.729 --> 00:17:45.563
MAN: We must vote to levy!

196
00:17:45.731 --> 00:17:48.649
<i>(SHOUTING)</i>

197
00:17:49.902 --> 00:17:52.028
<i>(CLEARS THROAT)</i>

198
00:18:00.079 --> 00:18:02.580
Twenty-eight to 12!
The levy passed!

199
00:18:02.748 --> 00:18:06.209
<i>(CHEERING)</i>

200
00:18:11.256 --> 00:18:13.132
<i>(INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE)</i>

201
00:18:32.653 --> 00:18:34.654
You intend to enlist
without my permission?

202
00:18:35.239 --> 00:18:36.697
Yes, I do.

203
00:18:42.412 --> 00:18:46.332
Father, I thought you were
a man of principle.

204
00:18:50.337 --> 00:18:53.673
When you have a family of your own,
perhaps you'll understand.

205
00:18:56.301 --> 00:18:59.512
When I have a family of my own,
I won't hide behind them.

206
00:19:04.643 --> 00:19:06.686
<i>(INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE)</i>

207
00:19:15.737 --> 00:19:19.615
He's as imprudent as his father was
at his age.

208
00:19:19.992 --> 00:19:21.617
Regrettably so.

209
00:19:23.579 --> 00:19:26.122
I'll see to it that he
serves under me.

210
00:19:27.166 --> 00:19:31.335
Make him a clerk or quartermaster,
something of that sort.

211
00:19:33.839 --> 00:19:35.381
Good luck.

212
00:20:00.282 --> 00:20:02.742
GABRIEL: <i>Dear Thomas,</i>
<i>Though many seasons have passed,</i>

213
00:20:02.951 --> 00:20:07.205
<i>it seems like only yesterday when we</i>
<i>last saw each other in Charles Town.</i>

214
00:20:07.873 --> 00:20:11.000
<i>lt was with great sadness that I learned
of its recent fall to the British</i>

215
00:20:11.210 --> 00:20:13.044
<i>under General Cornwallis.</i>

216
00:20:17.049 --> 00:20:19.050
<i>l received a letter</i>
<i>from Aunt Charlotte</i>

217
00:20:19.259 --> 00:20:22.678
<i>saying she closed her home</i>
<i>in Charles Town after the city fell</i>

218
00:20:22.846 --> 00:20:25.765
<i>and moved to her plantation</i>
<i>on the Santee.</i>

219
00:20:30.854 --> 00:20:33.231
<i>(COMMANDER SHOUTING)</i>

220
00:20:36.068 --> 00:20:40.696
GABRIEL: <i>Here in the north, our campaign has</i>
<i>been marked by defeat and privation.</i>

221
00:20:42.407 --> 00:20:44.575
<i>Our losses have been grievous.</i>

222
00:20:50.832 --> 00:20:55.086
<i>My good friend, Peter Cuppin,</i>
<i>fell at Elizabethtown.</i>

223
00:20:56.505 --> 00:20:58.256
No!

224
00:21:02.010 --> 00:21:04.553
GABRIEL: <i>His death has
been difficult to bear.</i>

225
00:21:17.526 --> 00:21:19.944
<i>We are told that soon we will march
south with General Gates</i>

226
00:21:20.153 --> 00:21:22.947
<i>to fight the Redcoats</i>
<i>under Cornwallis.</i>

227
00:21:26.076 --> 00:21:27.118
Thank you, sir.

228
00:21:40.966 --> 00:21:42.550
<i>l envy you</i>

229
00:21:42.759 --> 00:21:47.263
<i>your youth and distance from this</i>
<i>cruel conflict of which I am a part.</i>

230
00:21:48.682 --> 00:21:51.475
"But I consider myself fortunate
to be serving the cause of Liberty.

231
00:21:52.894 --> 00:21:54.895
And though I fear death,

232
00:21:55.147 --> 00:21:57.815
each day in prayer I reaffirm
my willingness, if necessary,

233
00:21:58.025 --> 00:22:00.359
to give my life in its service.

234
00:22:01.403 --> 00:22:02.445
Pray for me.

235
00:22:03.989 --> 00:22:06.365
But above all, pray for the cause.

236
00:22:07.492 --> 00:22:09.368
Your loving brother, Gabriel."

237
00:22:45.655 --> 00:22:46.697
What are you doing?

238
00:22:53.455 --> 00:22:54.747
Turn around.

239
00:22:59.753 --> 00:23:01.754
Not yet, Thomas.

240
00:23:02.172 --> 00:23:03.214
When?

241
00:23:03.673 --> 00:23:05.716
<i>(EXHALES SHARPLY)</i>

242
00:23:08.345 --> 00:23:09.387
Seventeen.

243
00:23:10.972 --> 00:23:13.724
That's two years.
It's already been two.

244
00:23:13.975 --> 00:23:16.977
The war could be over by then.
God willing.

245
00:23:21.274 --> 00:23:23.943
All right. Seventeen.

246
00:23:27.406 --> 00:23:28.614
All right.

247
00:23:36.123 --> 00:23:37.623
Put it back, please.

248
00:23:41.795 --> 00:23:43.254
Father?

249
00:23:44.673 --> 00:23:46.841
What happened at Fort Wilderness?

250
00:23:50.095 --> 00:23:51.345
Put it away.

251
00:23:57.394 --> 00:23:58.602
WILLIAM: Throw it faster.

252
00:23:58.770 --> 00:24:00.855
SAMUEL: You throw it faster.
You're the one--

253
00:24:01.648 --> 00:24:02.982
<i>(GRUNTING)</i>

254
00:24:03.150 --> 00:24:04.608
<i>(HORSE WHINNIES)</i>

255
00:24:04.776 --> 00:24:06.569
Whoa.

256
00:24:08.196 --> 00:24:10.156
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

257
00:24:12.868 --> 00:24:16.370
Margaret, you go get your brothers
back up here right now.

258
00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:24.980
Back to the house. Come on.
Back to the house now.

259
00:25:25.273 --> 00:25:29.193
Come with me. Margaret, go now.

260
00:25:36.535 --> 00:25:37.826
They're going to come.

261
00:25:38.036 --> 00:25:40.871
Quiet. Sit down.

262
00:25:48.129 --> 00:25:51.674
<i>(DISTANT BOOMING)</i>

263
00:26:12.529 --> 00:26:14.029
Six-pounders.

264
00:26:14.531 --> 00:26:15.573
Lots of them.

265
00:26:16.491 --> 00:26:17.825
How far away?

266
00:26:18.785 --> 00:26:22.746
Oh, they're a long way off. They're most
likely heading the other direction.

267
00:26:24.541 --> 00:26:26.125
Put those in the house.

268
00:26:26.626 --> 00:26:29.086
- THOMAS: They might come this way.
- Thomas, must I tell you again?

269
00:26:32.591 --> 00:26:35.467
Let's all stay close in
to the house, all right?

270
00:26:40.682 --> 00:26:45.060
<i>(LOUDER BOOMING)</i>

271
00:26:53.069 --> 00:26:54.111
<i>(PANTING)</i>

272
00:26:55.655 --> 00:26:57.031
We're gonna have to fight them off.

273
00:26:57.574 --> 00:26:59.116
Won't Father do that?

274
00:27:00.160 --> 00:27:02.536
They'll probably kill us men...

275
00:27:04.414 --> 00:27:06.582
and do Lord-knows-what to you women.

276
00:27:06.833 --> 00:27:08.375
Nathan.

277
00:27:19.721 --> 00:27:22.973
<i>(CHILDREN CHATTERING)</i>

278
00:27:32.359 --> 00:27:33.400
<i>(GUN COCKS)</i>

279
00:27:34.986 --> 00:27:36.278
Slowly turn.

280
00:27:40.033 --> 00:27:41.075
GABRIEL: Father.

281
00:27:41.326 --> 00:27:42.951
<i>(GRUNTING)</i>

282
00:27:44.371 --> 00:27:45.663
Abigale!

283
00:27:46.456 --> 00:27:48.040
Water and bandages, fast.

284
00:27:50.001 --> 00:27:51.043
Ah!

285
00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:54.630
Easy.
The battle. Were you there?

286
00:27:55.256 --> 00:27:56.882
Have you seen any Redcoats?

287
00:27:57.092 --> 00:27:58.634
No, not yet.

288
00:27:59.094 --> 00:28:01.428
Abigale, the children, please.

289
00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:04.056
Children, come. Upstairs.

290
00:28:04.849 --> 00:28:06.850
<i>(GROANING)</i>

291
00:28:09.854 --> 00:28:12.231
GABRIEL: Gates marched us
straight at the Redcoats.

292
00:28:12.440 --> 00:28:16.193
Our lines broke. The British
Green Dragoons cut us to bits.

293
00:28:16.444 --> 00:28:18.654
I was given these dispatches.

294
00:28:19.072 --> 00:28:22.866
As I left, I saw
the Virginia Regulars surrender.

295
00:28:26.079 --> 00:28:27.955
The Dragoons rode into them.

296
00:28:29.708 --> 00:28:30.749
Killed them all.

297
00:28:32.085 --> 00:28:33.752
Over 200 men.

298
00:28:34.295 --> 00:28:36.755
<i>(EXHALES SHARPLY)</i> I have to get
these dispatches to Hillsborough.

299
00:28:37.006 --> 00:28:38.173
You're in no condition to ride.

300
00:28:38.425 --> 00:28:40.134
I can't stay here!
It's not safe for--

301
00:28:40.301 --> 00:28:42.928
<i>(SOLDIERS SHOUTING)</i>

302
00:28:43.513 --> 00:28:46.682
<i>(CANNONS BOOMING)</i>

303
00:29:14.002 --> 00:29:15.461
MAN: Fire!

304
00:29:15.628 --> 00:29:17.629
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

305
00:29:23.803 --> 00:29:25.262
MAN: Fire!

306
00:29:25.638 --> 00:29:27.598
<i>(GROANING)</i>

307
00:30:23.571 --> 00:30:25.405
<i>(HORSE WHINNIES)</i>

308
00:30:45.885 --> 00:30:47.845
<i>(CHATTERING)</i>

309
00:30:48.012 --> 00:30:50.681
<i>(GROANING)</i>

310
00:31:49.032 --> 00:31:51.617
Thank you for the care
of His Majesty's soldiers.

311
00:31:52.327 --> 00:31:54.620
<i>(RIDERS APPROACH)</i>

312
00:32:22.732 --> 00:32:25.776
Lieutenant, have a detachment take
our wounded to our surgeons at Winnsboro.

313
00:32:26.277 --> 00:32:27.402
LIEUTENANT: Yes, sir.

314
00:32:29.238 --> 00:32:30.447
Fire the house and barns.

315
00:32:32.867 --> 00:32:36.036
Let it be known if you harbor
the enemy you will lose your home.

316
00:32:40.124 --> 00:32:42.000
By standing order
of His Majesty King George,

317
00:32:42.210 --> 00:32:45.671
all slaves of the American colonies
who fight for the Crown

318
00:32:45.922 --> 00:32:49.007
will be granted their freedom
with our victory.

319
00:32:49.175 --> 00:32:50.717
Sir.

320
00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:54.846
We're not slaves. We work this land.
We're freedmen.

321
00:32:55.056 --> 00:32:58.141
Well, then you're freedmen who will
have the opportunity and the privilege

322
00:32:58.393 --> 00:33:00.560
of fighting in the king's army
aren't you?

323
00:33:06.484 --> 00:33:08.318
Rebel dispatches, sir.

324
00:33:14.742 --> 00:33:16.118
Who carried this?

325
00:33:25.378 --> 00:33:26.503
Who carried this?!

326
00:33:27.505 --> 00:33:28.547
I did, sir.

327
00:33:35.346 --> 00:33:37.347
I was wounded.
These people gave me care.

328
00:33:38.349 --> 00:33:40.726
They have nothing to do
with the dispatches.

329
00:33:43.688 --> 00:33:45.605
Take this one to Camden.
He is a spy.

330
00:33:45.815 --> 00:33:47.941
Hang him, put his body on display.

331
00:33:48.484 --> 00:33:50.360
He's a dispatch rider
and that's a marked case.

332
00:33:50.570 --> 00:33:53.238
Destroy the livestock.
Save the horses for the Dragoons.

333
00:33:53.990 --> 00:33:57.826
Colonel, this is a uniformed dispatch rider
carrying a marked case.

334
00:33:58.036 --> 00:33:59.369
He cannot be held as a spy.

335
00:33:59.579 --> 00:34:02.289
Well, we're not going to hold him.
We're going to hang him.

336
00:34:05.877 --> 00:34:07.419
Colonel--
Father!

337
00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:13.800
Oh, I see. He's your son.

338
00:34:14.802 --> 00:34:17.679
Perhaps you should've taught him
something of loyalty.

339
00:34:19.015 --> 00:34:22.350
Colonel, I beg you, please reconsider.
By the rules of war--

340
00:34:22.518 --> 00:34:27.022
"Rules of war"? Would you like a lesson, sir,
in the rules of war?

341
00:34:30.109 --> 00:34:31.651
Or perhaps your children would.

342
00:34:33.446 --> 00:34:35.405
<i>(GASPING)</i>

343
00:34:36.783 --> 00:34:38.325
No lesson is necessary.

344
00:34:41.496 --> 00:34:42.537
LIEUTENANT: Sir.

345
00:34:42.747 --> 00:34:44.706
What of the rebel wounded?

346
00:34:47.043 --> 00:34:48.335
Kill them.

347
00:34:53.257 --> 00:34:54.382
Father.

348
00:34:58.471 --> 00:35:00.263
Father, do something!

349
00:35:00.473 --> 00:35:01.515
Be quiet!

350
00:35:14.278 --> 00:35:16.154
Gabriel, run!
Thomas!

351
00:35:17.281 --> 00:35:18.323
Wait!

352
00:35:21.202 --> 00:35:28.959
No!

353
00:35:29.585 --> 00:35:31.086
Thomas.

354
00:35:33.464 --> 00:35:34.673
<i>(CHOKING)</i>

355
00:35:48.855 --> 00:35:50.730
Stupid boy.

356
00:35:56.737 --> 00:35:57.988
Captain.

357
00:36:02.910 --> 00:36:04.661
WILLIAM: Thomas!

358
00:36:09.625 --> 00:36:12.669
<i>(GROANING)</i>

359
00:36:59.926 --> 00:37:01.343
Come, child.

360
00:37:03.137 --> 00:37:05.597
I'm not leaving these children!

361
00:37:05.806 --> 00:37:07.182
Mercy!

362
00:37:08.476 --> 00:37:09.976
MAN: Get ready!

363
00:37:10.144 --> 00:37:11.186
Present!

364
00:37:11.354 --> 00:37:12.437
Fire!

365
00:37:54.272 --> 00:37:56.481
<i>(PANTING)</i>

366
00:37:56.649 --> 00:37:58.066
All of you, stay here.

367
00:38:33.477 --> 00:38:34.936
Nathan, Samuel.

368
00:38:39.734 --> 00:38:40.942
Margaret.

369
00:38:43.404 --> 00:38:45.905
I want you to hide in the fields
with William and Susan.

370
00:38:46.073 --> 00:38:48.908
If we're not back by sunset, I want you
to take them to your Aunt Charlotte's.

371
00:38:49.076 --> 00:38:51.494
- Is that clear?
- Yeah.

372
00:38:52.121 --> 00:38:53.246
Boys.

373
00:39:46.592 --> 00:39:47.884
It's a good spot.

374
00:39:49.261 --> 00:39:51.429
Boys, listen to me.

375
00:39:51.889 --> 00:39:53.598
I'll fire first.

376
00:39:55.684 --> 00:39:58.603
I want you two to start with the officers
and work your way down.

377
00:39:58.813 --> 00:40:00.522
Can you tell the difference?

378
00:40:00.689 --> 00:40:01.731
Yes, Father.

379
00:40:01.982 --> 00:40:03.775
- Yes, Father.
- Good.

380
00:40:04.360 --> 00:40:06.945
Samuel, after your first shot,
I want you to reload for Nathan.

381
00:40:08.030 --> 00:40:09.072
Now,

382
00:40:09.323 --> 00:40:11.908
if anything should happen to me,
I want you two to drop your weapons

383
00:40:12.076 --> 00:40:13.952
and I want you to run
as quickly as you can.

384
00:40:14.161 --> 00:40:16.621
Hide in the brush. Make your way home,
get your brother and your sisters

385
00:40:16.831 --> 00:40:19.582
and you take them to
your Aunt Charlotte's. Understood?

386
00:40:21.127 --> 00:40:22.752
What did I tell you fellas
about shooting?

387
00:40:23.295 --> 00:40:24.587
TOGETHER: Aim small, miss small.

388
00:40:25.047 --> 00:40:26.756
Aim small, miss small.

389
00:40:27.967 --> 00:40:29.134
Boys...

390
00:40:29.635 --> 00:40:30.969
Samuel...

391
00:40:31.345 --> 00:40:32.679
steady.

392
00:41:20.227 --> 00:41:22.687
Lord, make me fast and accurate.

393
00:41:24.231 --> 00:41:32.572
Aim small, miss small.

394
00:41:46.003 --> 00:41:48.004
- REDCOAT 1: On the right!
- REDCOAT 2: To the left!

395
00:41:53.594 --> 00:41:56.221
- Ugh!
= REDCOAT 3: Behind us! On the ridge!

396
00:42:00.726 --> 00:42:02.060
Form right!

397
00:42:04.063 --> 00:42:05.104
To the right!

398
00:42:07.191 --> 00:42:08.566
About face!

399
00:42:09.276 --> 00:42:10.485
Ugh!

400
00:42:11.403 --> 00:42:12.904
REDCOAT 4: On the right to the rear!

401
00:42:14.240 --> 00:42:15.740
To the right!

402
00:42:15.908 --> 00:42:16.950
Fire!

403
00:42:18.244 --> 00:42:20.411
- MAN 4: Reload!
- MAN 5: Reload!

404
00:42:22.289 --> 00:42:23.540
Ah!

405
00:42:39.515 --> 00:42:40.890
REDCOAT 5: Behind you!

406
00:42:42.101 --> 00:42:43.351
Ah!

407
00:42:45.813 --> 00:42:47.480
REDCOAT 5: Look on the rear!

408
00:42:50.609 --> 00:42:52.610
Ah!

409
00:43:03.539 --> 00:43:05.665
<i>(GRUNTING)</i>

410
00:43:33.819 --> 00:43:36.279
<i>(PANTING)</i>

411
00:44:00.137 --> 00:44:02.388
<i>(GRUNTING)</i>

412
00:44:15.486 --> 00:44:17.654
Ah!

413
00:44:27.414 --> 00:44:29.248
<i>(YELLING)</i>

414
00:47:15.207 --> 00:47:16.499
BENJAMIN: Lord,

415
00:47:17.584 --> 00:47:20.294
we pray that you accept this child

416
00:47:20.462 --> 00:47:23.464
and keep him at your side
with his mother.

417
00:47:24.633 --> 00:47:27.385
We ask that you embrace him

418
00:47:29.680 --> 00:47:34.141
and help us to understand the manner
in which your mercy works.

419
00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:37.395
And forgive us our sins.

420
00:47:37.563 --> 00:47:40.731
This we ask in your name.

421
00:47:40.899 --> 00:47:42.733
Amen.

422
00:48:07.676 --> 00:48:10.553
BORDON: Sir, we have the private
the Cherokee scouts brought in.

423
00:48:22.190 --> 00:48:23.482
Private?

424
00:48:23.734 --> 00:48:24.775
BORDON: Private.

425
00:48:24.985 --> 00:48:26.986
Colonel William Tavington,
Green Dragoons.

426
00:48:27.863 --> 00:48:30.156
What happened? Who did this?

427
00:48:31.074 --> 00:48:32.199
Him.

428
00:48:33.535 --> 00:48:34.911
It was mad.

429
00:48:35.787 --> 00:48:37.413
I couldn't tell you who it was.

430
00:48:37.664 --> 00:48:39.749
Calm down. Calm down, man.

431
00:48:40.375 --> 00:48:43.210
Twenty of His Majesty's soldiers
are dead.

432
00:48:43.420 --> 00:48:45.838
And I need to know how.

433
00:48:46.048 --> 00:48:48.299
He said there was--
Were you there?

434
00:48:48.675 --> 00:48:50.760
Then let him speak.

435
00:48:51.386 --> 00:48:54.764
Take your time and tell me.
How many were there?

436
00:48:54.973 --> 00:48:56.891
Were they militia?
Were they Regulars?

437
00:48:57.392 --> 00:48:59.727
I don't really remember how many.

438
00:49:02.147 --> 00:49:03.272
Maybe one.

439
00:49:05.484 --> 00:49:07.985
One man. Really?

440
00:49:08.278 --> 00:49:09.987
He was in the flank.

441
00:49:11.490 --> 00:49:13.157
All around us.

442
00:49:13.492 --> 00:49:14.992
Amongst us.

443
00:49:15.577 --> 00:49:18.204
I could barely see him.
He was there, and then he was gone.

444
00:49:18.372 --> 00:49:20.039
He just vanished.

445
00:49:21.208 --> 00:49:22.833
Sounds more like a ghost than a man.

446
00:49:23.001 --> 00:49:25.503
Yes. A ghost.

447
00:49:26.964 --> 00:49:28.673
He was like a ghost.

448
00:49:30.258 --> 00:49:31.592
Enough.

449
00:49:33.720 --> 00:49:36.430
Bordon? Take a patrol.

450
00:49:36.640 --> 00:49:39.600
See if we can't capture this ghost
before word of his exploits spread.

451
00:49:39.810 --> 00:49:42.728
- Who's this?
- Sir, this is Captain Wilkins.

452
00:49:42.938 --> 00:49:44.689
He was with the Loyalist Colonial Militia.

453
00:49:44.898 --> 00:49:46.440
I thought he might be of use.

454
00:49:46.942 --> 00:49:48.776
Another colonial.

455
00:49:49.236 --> 00:49:51.737
Tell me, Captain Wilkins,
where do your loyalties lie?

456
00:49:51.989 --> 00:49:53.072
To king and country, sir.

457
00:49:53.407 --> 00:49:55.908
Why should I trust a man
who'd betray his neighbors?

458
00:49:56.702 --> 00:49:59.745
Those neighbors of mine
who stand against England

459
00:49:59.955 --> 00:50:01.706
deserve to die a traitor's death.

460
00:50:02.833 --> 00:50:03.874
We'll see.

461
00:50:10.173 --> 00:50:11.674
Mr. Martin!

462
00:50:17.973 --> 00:50:19.640
WOMAN: Miss Charlotte!

463
00:50:31.236 --> 00:50:34.030
CHARLOTTE: You're safe now.
Try to sleep.

464
00:50:34.239 --> 00:50:36.991
Good night.

465
00:50:37.659 --> 00:50:38.951
NATHAN: Father?

466
00:50:39.161 --> 00:50:40.411
BENJAMIN: Yes.

467
00:50:41.371 --> 00:50:43.539
I killed those men.

468
00:50:44.750 --> 00:50:46.208
You did what I told you to do.

469
00:50:47.669 --> 00:50:50.796
You did what you had to.
There was no wrong in it.

470
00:50:53.300 --> 00:50:55.426
I'm glad I killed them.

471
00:50:58.972 --> 00:51:00.598
I'm glad.

472
00:51:10.358 --> 00:51:11.859
Get some rest.

473
00:51:19.534 --> 00:51:20.868
Samuel.

474
00:51:41.598 --> 00:51:44.934
You've done nothing for which
you should be ashamed.

475
00:51:46.812 --> 00:51:48.395
I've done nothing.

476
00:51:50.190 --> 00:51:52.274
And for that, I am ashamed.

477
00:52:32.399 --> 00:52:33.941
We'll go to Saint Helena.

478
00:52:34.401 --> 00:52:38.696
That's a free slave island
just north of Charles Town.

479
00:52:39.698 --> 00:52:41.157
We'll be right under
the British noses.

480
00:52:41.324 --> 00:52:44.702
They won't even think of looking--
I'm joining up with them.

481
00:52:45.328 --> 00:52:47.079
Gabriel.

482
00:52:48.957 --> 00:52:51.000
No. Your place is here now.

483
00:52:51.209 --> 00:52:53.377
I'm going back.
I'm a soldier, it's my duty.

484
00:52:54.296 --> 00:52:56.297
Your duty is to your family.

485
00:52:58.008 --> 00:52:59.884
Don't you walk away from me, boy!

486
00:53:00.051 --> 00:53:01.427
I'm sorry,
I'll find you when it's over.

487
00:53:01.636 --> 00:53:03.429
No, you're not going.
I forbid you to go!

488
00:53:03.638 --> 00:53:06.140
I'm not a child!
You're my child!

489
00:53:08.894 --> 00:53:10.227
Goodbye, Father.

490
00:53:11.396 --> 00:53:13.189
Gabriel.

491
00:53:13.857 --> 00:53:15.482
Thomas is dead.

492
00:53:16.151 --> 00:53:18.903
How many more have to die
before you'll heed my word?

493
00:53:40.508 --> 00:53:41.967
Yah, yah.

494
00:53:48.975 --> 00:53:50.976
I'm losing my family.

495
00:53:54.773 --> 00:53:56.857
When will you be back, Father?

496
00:53:57.817 --> 00:53:59.151
I don't know.

497
00:53:59.611 --> 00:54:00.945
Tomorrow?

498
00:54:01.321 --> 00:54:03.155
No, not tomorrow.

499
00:54:03.615 --> 00:54:05.366
You say your prayers.

500
00:54:05.575 --> 00:54:06.784
I will.

501
00:54:07.494 --> 00:54:11.121
Nathan, I want you to take care of your
brothers and sisters and your Aunt Charlotte.

502
00:54:11.498 --> 00:54:13.207
I'm depending on you.

503
00:54:14.209 --> 00:54:16.085
As I am on you, Samuel.

504
00:54:17.587 --> 00:54:18.712
All right.

505
00:54:25.595 --> 00:54:26.887
Susan...

506
00:54:29.182 --> 00:54:30.391
goodbye.

507
00:54:45.282 --> 00:54:46.532
Thank you.

508
00:55:24.195 --> 00:55:26.280
<i>(WHINNIES)</i>

509
00:55:31.244 --> 00:55:32.328
Yah! Yah!

510
00:55:46.843 --> 00:55:49.511
<i>(BOOMING)</i>

511
00:55:58.813 --> 00:56:01.523
<i>(MEN SHOUTING)</i>

512
00:56:54.619 --> 00:56:56.036
MAN: Halt!

513
00:57:00.375 --> 00:57:01.875
Make ready!

514
00:57:06.756 --> 00:57:08.340
Take aim!

515
00:57:12.887 --> 00:57:14.138
Fire!

516
00:57:15.432 --> 00:57:18.100
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

517
00:57:26.192 --> 00:57:27.943
I'm not going back.

518
00:57:28.611 --> 00:57:30.821
No, I didn't expect you would.

519
00:57:35.410 --> 00:57:37.744
That Gates is a damn fool.

520
00:57:39.664 --> 00:57:41.999
He spent too many years
in the British army.

521
00:57:42.292 --> 00:57:46.336
Going muzzle-to-muzzle with Redcoats
in open field. It's madness.

522
00:57:47.046 --> 00:57:48.172
MAN: Halt!

523
00:57:48.590 --> 00:57:50.382
Make ready!

524
00:57:50.967 --> 00:57:52.759
Present!

525
00:57:53.803 --> 00:57:55.053
Fire!

526
00:57:55.763 --> 00:57:58.140
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

527
00:58:16.618 --> 00:58:17.910
<i>(SIGHS)</i>

528
00:58:18.077 --> 00:58:20.454
This battle was over
before it began.

529
00:58:30.131 --> 00:58:31.381
MAN: Retreat!

530
00:58:32.050 --> 00:58:33.884
Retreat!

531
00:58:40.934 --> 00:58:43.560
These rustics are so inept.

532
00:58:43.895 --> 00:58:46.396
Nearly takes the honor out of victory.

533
00:58:47.273 --> 00:58:48.482
Nearly.

534
00:59:10.171 --> 00:59:12.256
Hello general, gentlemen.

535
00:59:12.423 --> 00:59:15.175
A glorious day
for His Majesty and England.

536
00:59:15.343 --> 00:59:17.469
CORNWALLIS: Colonel Tavington.

537
00:59:17.720 --> 00:59:20.597
Always too early.

538
00:59:20.848 --> 00:59:22.349
Always too eager for glory.

539
00:59:23.685 --> 00:59:26.436
For victory, my lord.

540
00:59:27.021 --> 00:59:28.897
I believe we took the field.

541
00:59:29.065 --> 00:59:31.692
Next time, you'll wait for my command.

542
00:59:32.277 --> 00:59:36.738
It appears that Colonel Tavington
prefers to follow his own commands.

543
00:59:36.906 --> 00:59:38.240
General O'Hara tells me

544
00:59:38.408 --> 00:59:42.286
you've earned the nickname
"The Butcher" among the populous.

545
00:59:42.453 --> 00:59:44.454
We'll discuss it tomorrow.

546
00:59:44.789 --> 00:59:47.416
Gentlemen, my compliments.

547
00:59:47.584 --> 00:59:50.043
- To a victory.
- MAN: Hear, hear.

548
01:00:00.305 --> 01:00:01.430
DOCTOR: Hold him firm.

549
01:00:01.598 --> 01:00:04.057
<i>(MEN SCREAMING)</i>

550
01:00:19.616 --> 01:00:21.241
BENJAMIN: Where's your commanding officer?

551
01:00:21.409 --> 01:00:22.701
SOLDIER: That tent there.

552
01:00:29.292 --> 01:00:31.126
It's a lost cause.

553
01:00:47.894 --> 01:00:49.436
BURWELL: Benjamin Martin.

554
01:00:49.646 --> 01:00:51.605
I'm in no mood for a lecture.

555
01:00:51.981 --> 01:00:54.274
Where's your General Gates now?

556
01:00:54.651 --> 01:00:58.779
The last anyone saw,
riding hard northeast,

557
01:00:59.030 --> 01:01:01.948
his staff 100 yards behind,
trying to catch up.

558
01:01:02.825 --> 01:01:04.534
So who's in command?

559
01:01:05.119 --> 01:01:06.495
I am.

560
01:01:07.413 --> 01:01:08.830
I think.

561
01:01:09.999 --> 01:01:11.375
What are my orders?

562
01:01:16.297 --> 01:01:19.508
We're a breath away from losing
this war, Benjamin.

563
01:01:22.303 --> 01:01:25.347
In the north, Washington
is reeling from Morristown.

564
01:01:25.556 --> 01:01:28.225
He's running and hiding
from 12,000 Redcoats.

565
01:01:28.476 --> 01:01:31.019
In the south, Cornwallis
has broken our back.

566
01:01:31.229 --> 01:01:34.481
Captured over 5000 of our troops
when he took Charles Town.

567
01:01:34.732 --> 01:01:37.859
And he destroyed the only army
between him and New York.

568
01:01:39.570 --> 01:01:43.031
So now there's nothing to stop him
from heading north to finish off Washington.

569
01:01:43.241 --> 01:01:47.160
Unless we can keep Cornwallis
in the south till the French arrive.

570
01:01:48.246 --> 01:01:51.123
They've promised a fleet
and 10,000 troops.

571
01:01:51.374 --> 01:01:52.999
When?

572
01:01:53.209 --> 01:01:56.461
Uh, six months at the earliest.

573
01:01:56.713 --> 01:01:59.047
You actually trust the French
to keep their word?

574
01:01:59.257 --> 01:02:00.716
VILLENEUVE: <i>Absolument.</i>

575
01:02:02.927 --> 01:02:05.595
BURWELL: Benjamin Martin.
Major Jean Villeneuve.

576
01:02:05.763 --> 01:02:08.515
French Seventh Light Foot.
He's here to help train the militia.

577
01:02:09.434 --> 01:02:12.728
The hero of Fort Wilderness.
Your reputation precedes you.

578
01:02:17.608 --> 01:02:20.736
You really expect to hold Cornwallis here
using just militia?

579
01:02:20.987 --> 01:02:23.238
Not me. You.

580
01:02:25.533 --> 01:02:27.451
Harry, they're not soldiers,
they're farmers.

581
01:02:27.618 --> 01:02:29.828
They'd be better off letting
the British just march through.

582
01:02:30.496 --> 01:02:33.165
They'd be better off,
but the cause wouldn't.

583
01:02:34.250 --> 01:02:36.293
How many men does Cornwallis have
under his command?

584
01:02:36.669 --> 01:02:38.754
Eight thousand infantry.

585
01:02:38.963 --> 01:02:41.381
Around 600 cavalry.

586
01:02:41.591 --> 01:02:44.176
I'm giving you a field commission
as a colonel.

587
01:02:44.594 --> 01:02:47.429
Might I request, sir, that you transfer
my son here under my command?

588
01:02:47.638 --> 01:02:48.972
- Sir, no, I--
- No.

589
01:02:49.182 --> 01:02:50.515
That's done.

590
01:02:54.020 --> 01:02:55.145
Thank you.

591
01:02:57.106 --> 01:02:59.107
Colonel, I've been a soldier now
for two years.

592
01:02:59.317 --> 01:03:01.777
As a scout, horseman,
marksman, scavenger.

593
01:03:01.986 --> 01:03:03.028
- Is that so?
- Yes, sir.

594
01:03:03.196 --> 01:03:04.529
I'd be of better use with Regulars.

595
01:03:04.739 --> 01:03:06.865
Where'd you learn all that riding,
shooting, scavenging?

596
01:03:07.074 --> 01:03:08.742
My father taught me.

597
01:03:10.745 --> 01:03:12.329
Teach you any humility?

598
01:03:12.997 --> 01:03:14.748
He tried. It didn't take.

599
01:03:16.083 --> 01:03:19.711
He also taught you every deer path and
swamp trail between here and Charles Town,

600
01:03:19.921 --> 01:03:21.671
which is why he asked
for your transfer.

601
01:03:22.340 --> 01:03:24.966
We'll put the word out.
Start on the south side of--

602
01:03:25.218 --> 01:03:27.427
We can cover more ground
if we split up.

603
01:03:31.015 --> 01:03:34.559
Very well, corporal. You take
Harrisville, Pembroke, Wakefield.

604
01:03:34.769 --> 01:03:38.104
I'll start on the north side.
We'll meet at the mission in Black Swamp.

605
01:03:38.314 --> 01:03:39.940
Yes, sir.

606
01:03:42.902 --> 01:03:44.069
BENJAMIN: And corporal...

607
01:03:45.780 --> 01:03:47.280
be careful.

608
01:03:49.575 --> 01:03:50.784
Yes, sir.

609
01:03:53.704 --> 01:03:55.539
<i>(SIGHS)</i>

610
01:03:55.706 --> 01:03:57.207
You have children?

611
01:04:01.921 --> 01:04:03.296
French.

612
01:04:27.405 --> 01:04:31.783
It skirts the mountain and then extends down
towards the headwater here

613
01:04:32.034 --> 01:04:35.579
and right across to the far bank
of the Ohio River.

614
01:04:36.038 --> 01:04:37.247
It's 100,000 acres.

615
01:04:37.456 --> 01:04:39.749
It's an imposing land grant, my lord.

616
01:04:39.959 --> 01:04:42.627
You will be a country unto yourself.

617
01:04:46.340 --> 01:04:48.049
His Majesty is most generous.

618
01:04:50.845 --> 01:04:54.806
Though, of course, your service in this war
more than warrants such a gift.

619
01:04:55.641 --> 01:05:00.395
Yes, this is how His Majesty
rewards those

620
01:05:00.605 --> 01:05:02.689
who fight for him as gentlemen.

621
01:05:02.940 --> 01:05:06.985
I dare to presume my own meagre contributions
will be rewarded one day.

622
01:05:07.194 --> 01:05:09.279
You may presume too much.

623
01:05:09.947 --> 01:05:13.491
His Majesty, like history, judges us
not only by the outcome of the war

624
01:05:13.743 --> 01:05:15.827
but the manner in which
it was fought.

625
01:05:16.162 --> 01:05:17.913
- My lord?
- We serve the Crown,

626
01:05:18.080 --> 01:05:19.873
and we must conduct ourselves accordingly.

627
01:05:20.791 --> 01:05:22.792
Surrendering troops
will be given quarter.

628
01:05:23.169 --> 01:05:25.337
These brutal tactics must stop.

629
01:05:26.088 --> 01:05:28.423
Is it not enough that I have
never lost a battle?

630
01:05:28.633 --> 01:05:29.799
You serve me,

631
01:05:30.009 --> 01:05:34.346
and the manner in which you serve me
reflects upon me!

632
01:05:35.473 --> 01:05:38.975
I would've thought that a gentleman
from a family as esteemed as yours

633
01:05:39.185 --> 01:05:40.685
would understand that.

634
01:05:42.563 --> 01:05:45.482
My late father squandered any esteem
in which we were held,

635
01:05:45.691 --> 01:05:47.567
along with my inheritance.

636
01:05:51.030 --> 01:05:53.657
I advance myself
only through victory.

637
01:05:53.866 --> 01:05:57.202
You advance yourself
only through my good graces.

638
01:05:58.913 --> 01:06:00.997
These Colonials are our brethren.

639
01:06:01.207 --> 01:06:06.002
And when this conflict is over,
we will reestablish commerce with them.

640
01:06:06.504 --> 01:06:08.421
Do you understand, colonel?

641
01:06:09.715 --> 01:06:11.424
Perfectly, my lord.

642
01:06:24.230 --> 01:06:29.234
<i>(CHURCH CHOIR SINGS)</i>

643
01:06:54.343 --> 01:06:57.470
Reverend, with your permission,
I'd like to make an announcement.

644
01:06:57.888 --> 01:07:00.765
Young man, this is a house of God.

645
01:07:01.392 --> 01:07:04.144
I understand that, reverend.
I apologize.

646
01:07:05.771 --> 01:07:08.898
The South Carolina Militia
is being called up.

647
01:07:09.233 --> 01:07:11.109
I'm here to enlist every man willing.

648
01:07:12.528 --> 01:07:13.570
REVEREND: Son,

649
01:07:14.071 --> 01:07:15.905
we are here to pray

650
01:07:16.115 --> 01:07:18.950
for the souls of those men
hanging outside.

651
01:07:19.160 --> 01:07:21.036
Yes, pray for them.

652
01:07:21.287 --> 01:07:23.580
But honor them
by taking up arms with us.

653
01:07:25.416 --> 01:07:27.459
And bring more suffering to this town?

654
01:07:27.835 --> 01:07:31.504
If King George can hang those men,
our friends, he can hang any one of us.

655
01:07:33.549 --> 01:07:34.716
Dan Scott,

656
01:07:34.925 --> 01:07:38.511
barely a week ago, I heard you rail
for two hours about independence.

657
01:07:38.679 --> 01:07:40.472
<i>(CHATTERING)</i>

658
01:07:41.223 --> 01:07:43.808
Mr. Hardwick, how many times
have I heard you

659
01:07:44.018 --> 01:07:46.561
speak of freedom
at my father's table?

660
01:07:48.105 --> 01:07:51.441
Half the men in this church,
including you, Father,

661
01:07:52.693 --> 01:07:54.486
and you, reverend,

662
01:07:54.945 --> 01:07:57.906
are as ardent patriots as I.

663
01:08:02.578 --> 01:08:07.082
Will you now, when you are needed most,
stop at only words?

664
01:08:07.541 --> 01:08:09.375
Is that the sort of men you are?

665
01:08:18.969 --> 01:08:21.262
I ask only that you act
upon the beliefs

666
01:08:21.472 --> 01:08:24.432
of which you have so strongly spoken,

667
01:08:25.226 --> 01:08:28.311
and in which you so strongly believe.

668
01:08:40.533 --> 01:08:41.950
Who's with us?

669
01:09:43.804 --> 01:09:44.846
Mr. Howard.

670
01:09:46.015 --> 01:09:47.056
Sir,

671
01:09:47.516 --> 01:09:49.767
may I have permission
to write to Anne?

672
01:09:51.270 --> 01:09:52.604
Eh?

673
01:09:53.564 --> 01:09:56.733
- May I have permission to write Anne?
- ANNE: Yes.

674
01:09:57.735 --> 01:09:59.319
You have permission

675
01:09:59.612 --> 01:10:01.571
to write me.

676
01:10:02.031 --> 01:10:03.948
Oh, write her.

677
01:10:05.409 --> 01:10:06.743
Very well.

678
01:10:08.787 --> 01:10:09.954
Thank you, sir.

679
01:10:12.499 --> 01:10:13.791
Reverend?

680
01:10:20.633 --> 01:10:22.759
A shepherd must tend his flock.

681
01:10:24.053 --> 01:10:27.513
And, at times, fight off the wolves.

682
01:10:55.084 --> 01:10:57.001
<i>(MEN SHOUTING AND LAUGHING)</i>

683
01:11:06.178 --> 01:11:09.472
Are you sure this is the right place
to recruit for a militia?

684
01:11:16.855 --> 01:11:18.523
God save King George!

685
01:11:29.910 --> 01:11:31.995
<i>(MEN YELLING)</i>

686
01:11:38.168 --> 01:11:40.169
I think we came to the right place.

687
01:11:46.844 --> 01:11:47.885
Any bounty?

688
01:11:48.053 --> 01:11:49.637
BENJAMIN: No scalp money this time, Rollins.

689
01:11:49.888 --> 01:11:54.142
But you can keep or sell me the muskets
and gear of any Redcoat you kill.

690
01:12:06.196 --> 01:12:08.740
They hanged my brother
down in Acworth.

691
01:12:09.616 --> 01:12:12.201
Every damned one of them Redcoats
deserves to die.

692
01:12:12.411 --> 01:12:13.995
Sign on up.
With all my ailments,

693
01:12:14.204 --> 01:12:17.206
I wouldn't make it through
the first skirmish. No, sir.

694
01:12:17.416 --> 01:12:20.335
But you can have my Negro.
He'll fight in my stead.

695
01:12:20.544 --> 01:12:22.170
Occam! Get over here.

696
01:12:23.505 --> 01:12:27.050
He ain't overly smart.
He's strong as a bull.

697
01:12:27.384 --> 01:12:28.426
Can you write?

698
01:12:29.428 --> 01:12:31.179
No, no, sir.

699
01:12:31.472 --> 01:12:33.097
- Well, then, make your mark.
- OLD MAN: Why?

700
01:12:33.640 --> 01:12:35.308
I just signed him over to you.

701
01:12:35.517 --> 01:12:37.685
If you're willing,
I'd like you to make your mark.

702
01:12:44.485 --> 01:12:45.526
That'll do.

703
01:12:51.033 --> 01:12:52.575
I'll kill me some Redcoats.

704
01:12:53.494 --> 01:12:54.827
I believe you would.

705
01:12:55.204 --> 01:12:56.371
How old are you?

706
01:12:56.622 --> 01:12:59.207
BILLINGS: Not quite old enough.
But his time will come.

707
01:12:59.416 --> 01:13:01.918
John Billings.
I was hoping you'd turn up.

708
01:13:02.127 --> 01:13:04.629
There's a story going around
about some 20 Redcoats

709
01:13:04.880 --> 01:13:07.507
got killed by a ghost
or some damn thing.

710
01:13:07.716 --> 01:13:09.384
Carried a Cherokee tomahawk.

711
01:13:11.470 --> 01:13:14.514
Aren't you a little old to be
believing in ghost stories?

712
01:13:37.162 --> 01:13:40.915
<i>(MEN CHATTERING AND LAUGHING)</i>

713
01:14:20.706 --> 01:14:22.331
How many did you get?

714
01:14:22.833 --> 01:14:23.875
Twelve.

715
01:14:24.626 --> 01:14:25.668
Good.

716
01:14:26.712 --> 01:14:29.547
These men, they're not the sort we need.

717
01:14:32.843 --> 01:14:34.969
They're exactly the sort we need.

718
01:14:36.180 --> 01:14:38.306
They've fought this kind of war before.

719
01:14:42.019 --> 01:14:44.020
What about me?
Am I one of that sort?

720
01:14:44.521 --> 01:14:45.813
Hell, no.

721
01:14:46.315 --> 01:14:48.399
You're the sort that gives
that sort a bad name.

722
01:14:54.114 --> 01:14:57.408
I want accuracy and precision.

723
01:14:57.868 --> 01:14:59.035
Make ready!

724
01:15:03.874 --> 01:15:05.333
Take aim!

725
01:15:10.506 --> 01:15:11.839
Fire!

726
01:15:12.674 --> 01:15:15.843
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

727
01:15:51.338 --> 01:15:52.630
GABRIEL: <i>Dear Anne,</i>

728
01:15:52.881 --> 01:15:54.924
<i>Our force continues to grow.</i>

729
01:15:55.133 --> 01:15:59.595
<i>As long as we continue to fight,</i>
<i>others will come to fight beside us.</i>

730
01:15:59.805 --> 01:16:02.848
<i>l long to see you and speak to you.</i>

731
01:16:03.058 --> 01:16:05.643
<i>l'm hopeful that our duties</i>
<i>will bring me near you.</i>

732
01:16:05.852 --> 01:16:10.147
<i>Until then, I am and will remain</i>
<i>most affectionately yours.</i>

733
01:16:10.357 --> 01:16:11.399
<i>Gabriel.</i>

734
01:16:18.949 --> 01:16:20.074
<i>(GUNSHOT)</i>

735
01:16:20.242 --> 01:16:21.659
- <i>(SCREAMING)</i>
- <i>(WHINNYING)</i>

736
01:16:31.753 --> 01:16:33.254
Go!

737
01:16:37.801 --> 01:16:39.343
REDCOAT: We surrender!
We surrend--! Ah!

738
01:16:41.555 --> 01:16:42.930
REVEREND: No! God, stop!

739
01:16:43.140 --> 01:16:44.599
For the love of God, we--

740
01:16:45.809 --> 01:16:47.476
These men were about to surrender!

741
01:16:49.479 --> 01:16:50.813
VILLENEUVE: Perhaps.

742
01:16:51.064 --> 01:16:52.189
We will never know.

743
01:16:52.566 --> 01:16:53.608
This is murder!

744
01:16:54.192 --> 01:16:57.278
Hell, reverend, they're Redcoats.
They've earned it.

745
01:17:00.032 --> 01:17:02.533
We are better men than that.
What do you know about war?

746
01:17:02.701 --> 01:17:04.201
I know the difference
between fighting--

747
01:17:04.411 --> 01:17:06.495
MAN: You go back to church!

748
01:17:06.705 --> 01:17:07.955
Quiet!

749
01:17:09.791 --> 01:17:11.125
He's right.

750
01:17:11.376 --> 01:17:15.504
In the future, full quarter will be given
to British wounded and any who surrender.

751
01:17:15.672 --> 01:17:17.256
The British men of war
gave no such quarter

752
01:17:17.424 --> 01:17:19.425
when they fired on a ship
carrying my wife and daughters.

753
01:17:20.469 --> 01:17:23.804
I watched from 200 yards off
as they were burned alive.

754
01:17:24.556 --> 01:17:26.140
You have my sympathy,
but my order stands.

755
01:17:26.308 --> 01:17:27.391
Damn your sympathy.

756
01:17:28.185 --> 01:17:30.436
Who are you to give such an order?

757
01:17:31.271 --> 01:17:34.398
I know what you and your men did
to my countrymen at Fort Wilderness.

758
01:17:37.069 --> 01:17:40.321
We're militia.
This is not regular army.

759
01:17:41.406 --> 01:17:43.908
Every man here is free
to come and go as he pleases.

760
01:17:44.117 --> 01:17:45.409
But while you're here,

761
01:17:45.619 --> 01:17:48.120
you will obey my command
or I will have you shot.

762
01:17:52.751 --> 01:17:54.585
- <i>(BARKING)</i>
- Damn dogs!

763
01:17:54.753 --> 01:17:57.046
Shoot the damn things!
Stay that pistol.

764
01:17:57.547 --> 01:17:59.423
They won't let anybody near the wagon.

765
01:18:05.430 --> 01:18:06.681
DAN: Rum, Madeira.

766
01:18:06.848 --> 01:18:08.391
BILLINGS: No wonder they were guarding it.

767
01:18:08.558 --> 01:18:11.352
- Officers' uniforms.
- MAN: What you think all this is worth?

768
01:18:12.813 --> 01:18:16.148
It's the personal correspondence
of Lord Cornwallis.

769
01:18:18.485 --> 01:18:19.527
This is his journal.

770
01:18:20.987 --> 01:18:25.032
I say we drink the wine, eat the dogs
and use the papers for musket wadding.

771
01:18:25.325 --> 01:18:26.659
Eat the dogs?

772
01:18:26.868 --> 01:18:27.910
TOGETHER: Yeah.

773
01:18:28.078 --> 01:18:29.620
- Dog is a fine meal.
- Uh-huh.

774
01:18:30.789 --> 01:18:32.331
Good Heavens.

775
01:18:35.043 --> 01:18:39.797
<i>(MUSIC PLAYS AND MEN SING)</i>)</i>

776
01:18:45.345 --> 01:18:47.346
BOY: I have some maps here for you.

777
01:18:48.682 --> 01:18:51.225
Put them down over there.
Thank you.

778
01:18:52.477 --> 01:18:54.812
Here. A proper musket for you.

779
01:18:55.021 --> 01:18:59.191
I don't know about you,
but I don't like the idea
of giving muskets to slaves.

780
01:18:59.401 --> 01:19:01.402
<i>(MEN LAUGH)</i>

781
01:19:01.862 --> 01:19:04.155
Your sense of freedom
is as pale as your skin.

782
01:19:10.954 --> 01:19:12.663
GABRIEL: Don't listen to them.

783
01:19:14.791 --> 01:19:17.376
If we win this war,
a lot of things will change.

784
01:19:18.253 --> 01:19:19.795
What will change?

785
01:19:21.214 --> 01:19:25.885
They call this the New World.
It's not. It's the same as the old.

786
01:19:28.472 --> 01:19:31.056
But we'll have a chance
to build a new world.

787
01:19:34.144 --> 01:19:38.647
A world where all men
are created equal under God.

788
01:19:39.399 --> 01:19:40.691
Equal.

789
01:19:42.068 --> 01:19:43.694
Sounds good.

790
01:19:44.863 --> 01:19:47.406
I've just been in the mind
of a genius.

791
01:19:49.993 --> 01:19:54.538
Cornwallis knows more about warfare than
we could hope to learn in a dozen lifetimes.

792
01:19:55.123 --> 01:19:56.457
That's cheerful news.

793
01:19:56.917 --> 01:20:01.253
His victories at Camden and
Charles Town were perfect. Perfect.

794
01:20:02.172 --> 01:20:04.131
And he knows it, what's more.

795
01:20:06.510 --> 01:20:07.885
Perhaps that's his weakness.

796
01:20:08.386 --> 01:20:09.553
Sir?

797
01:20:10.847 --> 01:20:12.056
Pride.

798
01:20:13.225 --> 01:20:14.642
Pride's a weakness.

799
01:20:15.185 --> 01:20:17.728
Personally, I would prefer stupidity.

800
01:20:20.023 --> 01:20:21.357
Pride will do.

801
01:20:29.950 --> 01:20:31.283
<i>(CHATTERING)</i>

802
01:20:32.577 --> 01:20:34.411
Finished, my lord.

803
01:20:34.871 --> 01:20:36.872
I've taken it in at the back,

804
01:20:37.082 --> 01:20:39.792
added wider epaulets
and looped gold braiding.

805
01:20:40.001 --> 01:20:42.795
- It's a horse blanket.
- TAVINGTON: I don't know, my lord.

806
01:20:43.296 --> 01:20:45.798
It's really quite nice.

807
01:20:45.966 --> 01:20:48.801
- Very nice, my lord.
- Very well. It's a nice horse blanket.

808
01:20:50.512 --> 01:20:53.430
Colonel Tavington, why, after six weeks,

809
01:20:53.640 --> 01:20:56.767
am I still attending a ball
in South Carolina,

810
01:20:56.977 --> 01:20:59.687
when I should be attending balls
in North Carolina?

811
01:20:59.855 --> 01:21:01.438
First, the theft of my personal baggage,

812
01:21:01.690 --> 01:21:04.483
including my memoirs, upon which
I spent countless hours.

813
01:21:04.985 --> 01:21:08.487
Then half the bridges and ferries
between here and Charles Town burned.

814
01:21:08.989 --> 01:21:11.866
Colonel, if you can't protect
our supply lines against militia,

815
01:21:12.075 --> 01:21:15.494
how do you intend doing so against
the Regulars or the French?

816
01:21:15.704 --> 01:21:18.330
They won't fight like Regulars.
We can't find them.

817
01:21:18.540 --> 01:21:21.041
Colonel, they're militia.

818
01:21:21.668 --> 01:21:24.003
They're farmers with pitchforks!

819
01:21:24.796 --> 01:21:27.256
They're rather more than that,
I'm afraid.

820
01:21:27.549 --> 01:21:30.509
Made so by their commander,
this ghost.

821
01:21:30.719 --> 01:21:33.554
Oh, ghost, ghost, ghost.

822
01:21:34.139 --> 01:21:36.849
You created this ghost, colonel.

823
01:21:37.559 --> 01:21:39.393
Your brutality has swelled his ranks.

824
01:21:39.603 --> 01:21:41.896
Without which, this ghost
would've disappeared

825
01:21:42.105 --> 01:21:44.106
and I'd be in North Carolina
or Virginia by now!

826
01:21:44.566 --> 01:21:46.025
In my defence, my lord--

827
01:21:46.234 --> 01:21:48.068
Oh, enough, enough.

828
01:21:48.778 --> 01:21:53.032
A fine soldier you are,
bested by a bedtime story.

829
01:21:54.367 --> 01:21:56.368
Give me the horse blanket.

830
01:21:59.539 --> 01:22:02.666
CORNWALLIS: O'Hara, our supply ship
appears to have arrived.

831
01:22:03.251 --> 01:22:04.668
Yes, my lord, it has.

832
01:22:04.878 --> 01:22:07.338
Then why am I still wearing
this rag?

833
01:22:07.547 --> 01:22:10.466
My lord, your replacement wardrobe
is aboard ship, but...

834
01:22:10.675 --> 01:22:14.762
Colonel Tavington thought it best to
secure our arms and munitions first.

835
01:22:14.930 --> 01:22:16.096
They are being unloaded now.

836
01:22:27.859 --> 01:22:29.276
You look good in that color.

837
01:22:31.404 --> 01:22:32.696
It stinks.

838
01:22:33.365 --> 01:22:34.490
Mm.

839
01:22:34.658 --> 01:22:36.492
Well, it's had a dead man in it.

840
01:22:36.826 --> 01:22:38.619
The beasts took your dogs too?

841
01:22:38.995 --> 01:22:40.245
Yes. Yes.

842
01:22:41.247 --> 01:22:44.416
Fine animals.
A gift from His Majesty.

843
01:22:45.335 --> 01:22:46.877
Dead now, for all I know.

844
01:22:47.337 --> 01:22:49.588
Is there no decency?

845
01:22:51.508 --> 01:22:53.550
<i>(GASPING)</i>

846
01:22:56.972 --> 01:22:58.639
Oh.

847
01:22:58.807 --> 01:23:02.559
Oh, fireworks. Lovely!

848
01:23:34.551 --> 01:23:36.093
Mr. Howard.

849
01:23:37.053 --> 01:23:39.221
I've come to call on Anne.

850
01:23:44.978 --> 01:23:48.105
I've come to call on Anne!

851
01:23:48.314 --> 01:23:50.524
Well, of course you
call yourself a man.

852
01:23:51.526 --> 01:23:54.903
Father, stop it. You heard him.

853
01:23:57.407 --> 01:23:58.449
Well...

854
01:23:59.117 --> 01:24:00.617
call on her.

855
01:24:26.394 --> 01:24:27.770
WOMAN: I'm nearly finished.

856
01:24:29.481 --> 01:24:31.315
You needn't worry, Father.

857
01:24:31.524 --> 01:24:32.983
Yeah, I know.

858
01:24:33.526 --> 01:24:37.404
I think bundling bags are a wonderful tradition.
I don't mind in the least.

859
01:24:37.572 --> 01:24:38.989
Ow!

860
01:24:39.157 --> 01:24:40.699
Be still.

861
01:24:41.409 --> 01:24:42.534
Tea?

862
01:24:43.536 --> 01:24:44.703
Please.

863
01:24:46.581 --> 01:24:47.623
There.

864
01:24:53.088 --> 01:24:54.421
Okay.

865
01:24:56.091 --> 01:24:57.382
Come, dear.

866
01:24:58.009 --> 01:24:59.468
<i>(GRUNTS)</i>

867
01:25:05.183 --> 01:25:07.184
Mm.

868
01:25:08.895 --> 01:25:10.354
It's very good.

869
01:25:13.358 --> 01:25:15.567
I'm pleased that you like it.

870
01:25:22.700 --> 01:25:24.243
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

871
01:25:24.410 --> 01:25:25.619
MOTHER: Peter.

872
01:25:26.329 --> 01:25:29.915
Don't worry. I sew better
than my mother did.

873
01:25:33.002 --> 01:25:34.503
I hope so.

874
01:25:40.718 --> 01:25:42.803
If you're just gonna stand there,

875
01:25:43.054 --> 01:25:44.805
why don't you read it for us?

876
01:25:45.056 --> 01:25:46.598
I can't read.

877
01:25:49.394 --> 01:25:50.686
I can.

878
01:25:53.898 --> 01:25:54.940
It says, "Take notice.

879
01:25:55.817 --> 01:25:59.361
By order of General Washington
and the Continental Congress,

880
01:25:59.612 --> 01:26:02.823
all bound slaves who give
minimum one year service

881
01:26:03.032 --> 01:26:04.533
in the Continental Army

882
01:26:05.368 --> 01:26:07.411
will be granted freedom

883
01:26:08.079 --> 01:26:11.874
and be paid a bounty of five shillings
for each month of service."

884
01:26:12.333 --> 01:26:13.709
DAN: Did you hear that?

885
01:26:13.918 --> 01:26:16.211
First they're gonna free them,
and then they're gonna pay them.

886
01:26:17.505 --> 01:26:19.756
Only another six months.

887
01:26:22.385 --> 01:26:24.219
What in the hell are you gonna do
with freedom?

888
01:26:35.607 --> 01:26:37.274
BILLINGS: I made this for you.

889
01:26:47.535 --> 01:26:49.620
Martha.

890
01:26:53.625 --> 01:26:55.417
Look after your mother.

891
01:27:00.924 --> 01:27:02.424
BENJAMIN: You know, Peter,

892
01:27:03.218 --> 01:27:04.718
I can't pay you for this.

893
01:27:04.928 --> 01:27:09.097
Benjamin, you pay me what you can,
when you can.

894
01:27:09.557 --> 01:27:10.974
I'm obliged.

895
01:27:12.310 --> 01:27:15.729
Gabriel sure reminds me
a lot of you.

896
01:27:16.856 --> 01:27:19.107
No, no, he's more like his mother.

897
01:27:20.985 --> 01:27:22.069
BENJAMIN: Corporal!

898
01:27:23.613 --> 01:27:25.489
Take your time. Dogs.

899
01:27:42.840 --> 01:27:43.882
Sir.

900
01:27:50.181 --> 01:27:51.223
<i>(CLEARS THROAT)</i>

901
01:28:30.179 --> 01:28:32.055
BENJAMIN: This road is closed.

902
01:28:32.473 --> 01:28:34.766
These wagons now belong
to the Continental Army.

903
01:28:35.226 --> 01:28:37.728
Ready arms!

904
01:28:39.939 --> 01:28:41.064
<i>(WHISTLES)</i>

905
01:28:50.533 --> 01:28:51.908
By twos!

906
01:29:01.044 --> 01:29:04.546
There's no need for your men to die.
Leave the wagons and go.

907
01:29:05.089 --> 01:29:06.798
This is the king's highway.

908
01:29:07.216 --> 01:29:09.926
And I advise you and your men
to make way.

909
01:29:16.851 --> 01:29:17.976
TAVINGTON: Charge!

910
01:29:18.978 --> 01:29:20.103
Fire!

911
01:29:21.397 --> 01:29:22.773
Retreat!

912
01:29:24.025 --> 01:29:25.108
<i>(SCREAMS)</i>

913
01:29:29.781 --> 01:29:31.198
MAN: Save yourselves!

914
01:29:31.407 --> 01:29:33.742
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

915
01:29:59.352 --> 01:30:00.394
BENJAMIN: Retreat!

916
01:30:18.955 --> 01:30:21.331
MAN 2: Ambush! Ambush!

917
01:30:54.907 --> 01:30:56.533
GABRIEL: I have the count.

918
01:30:57.994 --> 01:30:59.828
Twenty-two are dead.

919
01:31:00.538 --> 01:31:02.914
Eighteen wounded and 20 are missing.

920
01:31:03.207 --> 01:31:04.541
I'm through.

921
01:31:10.548 --> 01:31:12.215
He won't be the last to leave.

922
01:31:12.884 --> 01:31:15.135
Trust me.
Soon my countrymen will arrive.

923
01:31:15.344 --> 01:31:17.345
- The French army is--
- To hell with you.

924
01:31:17.513 --> 01:31:19.097
And to hell with the French army.

925
01:31:19.307 --> 01:31:20.432
BILLINGS: We don't need them.

926
01:31:20.683 --> 01:31:23.852
We got Benjamin Martin.
We know what he done to the French.

927
01:31:24.020 --> 01:31:26.271
<i>(MEN LAUGH)</i>

928
01:31:38.409 --> 01:31:39.743
Father.

929
01:31:40.286 --> 01:31:44.748
Wherever you go, men buy you drinks
because of what happened at Fort Wilderness.

930
01:31:47.126 --> 01:31:49.753
Strangers know more about you
than I do.

931
01:31:51.839 --> 01:31:53.507
Tell me what happened.

932
01:31:54.634 --> 01:31:59.387
Your mother asked me that question
around about the time you were born.

933
01:32:02.058 --> 01:32:04.768
I was drunk and foolish enough
to answer it.

934
01:32:11.400 --> 01:32:14.903
The French and the Cherokee
had raided along the Blue Ridge.

935
01:32:15.613 --> 01:32:18.698
The English settlers
had sought refuge at Fort Charles.

936
01:32:19.158 --> 01:32:22.369
By the time we got there,
the fort was abandoned.

937
01:32:23.663 --> 01:32:25.789
They'd left about a week before.

938
01:32:27.250 --> 01:32:29.834
But what we found was...

939
01:32:32.588 --> 01:32:33.838
Go on.

940
01:32:36.968 --> 01:32:40.470
They'd killed all the settlers,
the men.

941
01:32:42.515 --> 01:32:44.307
With the women and...

942
01:32:44.517 --> 01:32:46.726
some of the children, they had...

943
01:32:49.814 --> 01:32:52.774
We buried them all,
what was left of them.

944
01:32:55.444 --> 01:32:58.154
We caught up with them
at Fort Wilderness.

945
01:33:01.242 --> 01:33:02.826
We took our time.

946
01:33:05.162 --> 01:33:08.164
We cut them apart slowly.

947
01:33:08.833 --> 01:33:10.542
Piece by piece.

948
01:33:15.881 --> 01:33:17.882
I can see their faces.

949
01:33:21.137 --> 01:33:23.388
I can still hear their screams.

950
01:33:25.474 --> 01:33:28.810
All but two. We let them live.

951
01:33:30.187 --> 01:33:32.314
We placed the heads on a pallet

952
01:33:32.523 --> 01:33:35.150
and sent them back with the two
that lived to Fort Ambercon.

953
01:33:35.901 --> 01:33:39.195
The eyes, tongues, fingers,

954
01:33:39.447 --> 01:33:41.364
we put in baskets.

955
01:33:41.741 --> 01:33:44.701
Sent them down the Asheulot
to the Cherokee.

956
01:33:46.662 --> 01:33:50.165
Soon after, the Cherokee broke
their treaty with the French.

957
01:33:53.044 --> 01:33:55.003
That's how we justified it.

958
01:34:04.055 --> 01:34:05.430
We were...

959
01:34:07.058 --> 01:34:08.433
heroes.

960
01:34:10.853 --> 01:34:13.021
And men bought you drinks.

961
01:34:17.735 --> 01:34:21.738
Not a day goes by where I don't ask
God's forgiveness for what I did.

962
01:34:29.914 --> 01:34:33.917
Thomas was my brother,
as well as your son.

963
01:34:34.251 --> 01:34:38.213
You may not believe this, but I want
satisfaction as much as you do.

964
01:34:40.216 --> 01:34:42.300
But not at the expense of our cause.

965
01:34:43.511 --> 01:34:46.096
There will be a time for revenge.

966
01:34:47.056 --> 01:34:49.516
But until then, stay the course.

967
01:34:51.644 --> 01:34:54.854
That's what your mother used to say to me
when I'd get drunk or lose my temper.

968
01:34:55.064 --> 01:34:57.565
She'd say it to me
when I picked on Thomas.

969
01:35:03.572 --> 01:35:04.948
I miss him.

970
01:35:13.165 --> 01:35:16.000
<i>(SPLASHING)</i>

971
01:35:16.210 --> 01:35:18.378
<i>(GROANING)</i>

972
01:35:21.465 --> 01:35:24.592
The British got 18 of our men
at Fort Carolina.

973
01:35:25.010 --> 01:35:28.054
They'll be hung one at a time
until they give up the rest of us.

974
01:35:43.988 --> 01:35:45.280
Reverend,

975
01:35:45.489 --> 01:35:47.449
can you write a letter for me?

976
01:35:47.992 --> 01:35:50.577
- To my wife and boy.
- Yes, of course I will.

977
01:35:50.828 --> 01:35:53.705
But first let us pray.

978
01:36:08.596 --> 01:36:09.637
REDCOAT: <i>My lord,</i>

979
01:36:09.847 --> 01:36:11.723
there is a rider at the gates.

980
01:36:11.932 --> 01:36:14.851
A civilian carrying a white flag.

981
01:36:15.060 --> 01:36:16.644
I am occupied.

982
01:36:17.146 --> 01:36:19.522
He has a pair of dogs with him.

983
01:36:20.191 --> 01:36:22.567
Great Danes.

984
01:36:23.527 --> 01:36:24.569
REVEREND: <i>And dear Lord,</i>

985
01:36:24.737 --> 01:36:27.071
protect us in this,
our hour of need.

986
01:36:27.364 --> 01:36:30.950
This we ask in the name
of the Father, the Son...

987
01:36:31.160 --> 01:36:32.911
And the Holy Ghost.

988
01:36:38.042 --> 01:36:39.250
REDCOAT: <i>Wait here.</i>

989
01:36:39.543 --> 01:36:41.920
General Lord Cornwallis will be
with you shortly.

990
01:37:08.364 --> 01:37:10.448
<i>(SIGHS)</i>

991
01:37:25.381 --> 01:37:28.258
Jupiter, Mars. Come, boys.

992
01:37:31.178 --> 01:37:32.220
Come.

993
01:37:35.683 --> 01:37:39.602
My good boys. My brave boys.
You seem to be well fed.

994
01:37:41.480 --> 01:37:43.064
I thank you for that.

995
01:37:43.274 --> 01:37:45.817
I'm afraid I don't know your name.

996
01:37:46.068 --> 01:37:50.280
I'm a colonel in the Continental Army.
My rank should be sufficient for now.

997
01:37:51.156 --> 01:37:52.615
As you wish.

998
01:37:53.450 --> 01:37:54.659
Please be seated.

999
01:37:54.910 --> 01:37:55.952
Thank you.

1000
01:37:57.788 --> 01:38:01.499
Would you, as the initiating officer,
care to begin?

1001
01:38:02.084 --> 01:38:05.003
I will, unless of course,
you'd like to claim aggrieved status.

1002
01:38:05.212 --> 01:38:07.881
Yes, I would like to claim
aggrieved status.

1003
01:38:08.090 --> 01:38:09.799
Very well, sir. Proceed.

1004
01:38:10.134 --> 01:38:14.554
You have in your possession certain belongings
of mine including clothing,

1005
01:38:14.805 --> 01:38:18.349
furniture, personal effects
of a non-military nature,

1006
01:38:19.018 --> 01:38:20.768
which I'd like returned to me.

1007
01:38:21.186 --> 01:38:23.938
Indeed. I will do so
as soon as possible.

1008
01:38:25.524 --> 01:38:26.608
Thank you.

1009
01:38:26.942 --> 01:38:30.111
Now we come to the matter
of the specific targeting

1010
01:38:30.362 --> 01:38:32.238
of officers during engagements.

1011
01:38:32.698 --> 01:38:34.908
Colonel, you must know
that in civilized warfare,

1012
01:38:35.075 --> 01:38:40.455
officers in the field must not be accorded
inappropriate levels of hostile attention.

1013
01:38:41.457 --> 01:38:45.043
To your mind, what are appropriate
levels of hostile attention?

1014
01:38:45.252 --> 01:38:47.545
Imagine the chaos that would follow

1015
01:38:47.796 --> 01:38:51.007
from leaderless armies
having at each other.

1016
01:38:51.425 --> 01:38:54.636
There must be gentlemen
in command to lead,

1017
01:38:54.845 --> 01:38:58.181
and, where necessary,
restrain their men.

1018
01:38:59.183 --> 01:39:03.311
Restrain them from, say, targeting civilians.
Women, children and such.

1019
01:39:06.649 --> 01:39:07.857
That's a separate issue.

1020
01:39:08.067 --> 01:39:10.026
No, no, no. I consider them linked.

1021
01:39:10.694 --> 01:39:13.404
And as long as your soldiers
attack civilians,

1022
01:39:13.614 --> 01:39:16.699
I will order the shooting of officers
at the outset of every engagement.

1023
01:39:19.411 --> 01:39:21.704
And my men are excellent marksmen.

1024
01:39:25.960 --> 01:39:27.001
Very well.

1025
01:39:27.753 --> 01:39:30.546
- Now, let us move on to--
- Prisoner exchange.

1026
01:39:31.715 --> 01:39:32.757
Sir?

1027
01:39:33.550 --> 01:39:36.886
You have 18 of my men.
I want them back.

1028
01:39:39.306 --> 01:39:41.224
<i>(WHISPERING)</i>

1029
01:39:43.727 --> 01:39:48.398
I do have 18 criminals
under sentence of death,

1030
01:39:48.649 --> 01:39:51.150
but I hold no prisoners of war.

1031
01:39:51.694 --> 01:39:54.654
If that's your position,
18 of your officers will have to die.

1032
01:39:54.905 --> 01:39:56.990
Nineteen, if you hang me with my men.

1033
01:39:57.199 --> 01:39:58.241
My officers?

1034
01:39:58.450 --> 01:39:59.492
Sir.

1035
01:40:07.042 --> 01:40:10.003
Top of the ridge, to your left.
Just below the tree line.

1036
01:40:23.142 --> 01:40:24.308
Their names and ranks?

1037
01:40:24.643 --> 01:40:28.604
They refused to give me their names. But their ranks
are nine lieutenants, five captains, three majors

1038
01:40:28.814 --> 01:40:30.648
and one vert fat colonel
who called me...

1039
01:40:32.568 --> 01:40:34.277
<i>(IN BRITISH ACCENT)</i>
a cheeky fellow.

1040
01:40:34.737 --> 01:40:37.488
You know, this is not the conduct
of a gentleman.

1041
01:40:37.740 --> 01:40:40.783
If the conduct of your officers
is the measure of a gentleman,

1042
01:40:40.993 --> 01:40:43.077
I'll take that as a compliment.

1043
01:40:45.080 --> 01:40:46.247
Get my men.

1044
01:40:50.210 --> 01:40:52.962
- Arrange the exchange.
- My lord.

1045
01:40:53.213 --> 01:40:54.380
Thank you, sir.

1046
01:41:00.596 --> 01:41:02.597
<i>(WHINING)</i>

1047
01:41:25.871 --> 01:41:27.705
Release the prisoners!

1048
01:41:32.461 --> 01:41:34.629
- What is this?
- Prisoner exchange.

1049
01:41:34.838 --> 01:41:36.380
He has 18 of our officers.

1050
01:41:36.590 --> 01:41:38.508
Who is he? I recognize him.

1051
01:41:38.967 --> 01:41:40.635
He's the commander of the militia.

1052
01:41:42.096 --> 01:41:44.931
- Your ghost.
- Stay that sword, colonel!

1053
01:41:45.265 --> 01:41:47.558
He rode in under a white flag
for formal parley.

1054
01:41:47.893 --> 01:41:49.185
This is madness.

1055
01:41:49.853 --> 01:41:52.021
If you harm him,
you condemn our officers.

1056
01:41:53.565 --> 01:41:57.860
With respect, sir, he's killed as many
officers in the last two months.

1057
01:41:58.070 --> 01:42:02.573
He has shown no aggression here.
Hence he cannot be touched.

1058
01:42:02.866 --> 01:42:04.408
Has he not?

1059
01:42:07.996 --> 01:42:09.038
You!

1060
01:42:09.748 --> 01:42:12.708
So you're the ghost, are you?
I remember you!

1061
01:42:12.918 --> 01:42:15.002
On that farm! That stupid little boy!

1062
01:42:22.010 --> 01:42:23.386
Did he die?

1063
01:42:27.516 --> 01:42:28.599
You know,

1064
01:42:29.059 --> 01:42:31.686
it's an ugly business,
doing one's duty.

1065
01:42:31.895 --> 01:42:34.021
But just occasionally,

1066
01:42:34.690 --> 01:42:36.357
it's a real pleasure.

1067
01:42:40.445 --> 01:42:43.281
Before this war is over,
I'm going to kill you.

1068
01:42:46.910 --> 01:42:48.411
Why wait?

1069
01:42:57.754 --> 01:42:58.921
Soon.

1070
01:43:07.306 --> 01:43:08.681
<i>(WHISTLES)</i>

1071
01:43:31.955 --> 01:43:33.164
Move out!

1072
01:43:37.961 --> 01:43:41.297
But I still think it's imperative
to push north...

1073
01:43:44.468 --> 01:43:46.802
One of our captured officers,
my lord.

1074
01:43:51.683 --> 01:43:54.977
CORNWALLIS: <i>My reputation suffers</i>
<i>because of your incompetence!</i>

1075
01:43:55.187 --> 01:43:58.481
That man insults me!

1076
01:43:58.982 --> 01:44:02.693
Quite impressive for a farmer
with a pitchfork, wouldn't you say?

1077
01:44:09.868 --> 01:44:12.578
I want you to find that man.

1078
01:44:13.288 --> 01:44:15.331
I want you to capture him.

1079
01:44:16.750 --> 01:44:18.960
The man has the loyalty of the people.

1080
01:44:19.461 --> 01:44:21.837
They protect him.
Protect his family.

1081
01:44:22.047 --> 01:44:23.673
Protect the families of his men.

1082
01:44:25.092 --> 01:44:27.093
I can capture him for you.

1083
01:44:28.637 --> 01:44:32.515
But to do so requires the use
of tactics that are somewhat...

1084
01:44:33.767 --> 01:44:35.977
What was the word
your lordship used?

1085
01:44:37.854 --> 01:44:39.480
"Brutal," I think.

1086
01:44:48.198 --> 01:44:49.240
Go on.

1087
01:44:58.375 --> 01:45:00.918
I am prepared to do
what is necessary.

1088
01:45:01.253 --> 01:45:05.715
I alone will assume the full mantle
of responsibility for my actions,

1089
01:45:05.924 --> 01:45:08.050
free of the chain of command,

1090
01:45:08.260 --> 01:45:10.511
rendering you blameless.

1091
01:45:11.138 --> 01:45:12.513
However,

1092
01:45:12.889 --> 01:45:14.515
if I do this,

1093
01:45:14.725 --> 01:45:18.686
you and I both know that I can
never return to England with honor.

1094
01:45:21.940 --> 01:45:25.693
What, I wonder, is to become of me?

1095
01:45:33.285 --> 01:45:36.245
When this war is over here
in the Colonies,

1096
01:45:36.705 --> 01:45:38.497
the new aristocracy...

1097
01:45:40.584 --> 01:45:42.418
will be landowners.

1098
01:45:49.718 --> 01:45:52.345
Tell me about Ohio.

1099
01:45:57.976 --> 01:45:59.185
MAN: Make way.

1100
01:46:00.270 --> 01:46:01.520
As you were.

1101
01:46:04.649 --> 01:46:08.736
Wilkins. A plantation seven miles
from Wakefield, on the Santee,

1102
01:46:08.945 --> 01:46:11.238
east of Black Swamp.
Who lived there?

1103
01:46:13.325 --> 01:46:14.700
Benjamin Martin.

1104
01:46:14.910 --> 01:46:16.619
He's the ghost.

1105
01:46:17.537 --> 01:46:18.829
What do you know about him?

1106
01:46:18.997 --> 01:46:22.792
Hell, everything.
I could tell you the size of his boot.

1107
01:46:23.502 --> 01:46:27.380
Does he have family?
Where would he hide his children?

1108
01:46:36.264 --> 01:46:38.849
His wife's sister has a plantation.

1109
01:46:39.393 --> 01:46:40.893
It's not far.

1110
01:46:49.694 --> 01:46:52.696
<i>(RIDERS APPROACH)</i>

1111
01:47:14.678 --> 01:47:17.888
Aunt Charlotte.
Wake up, someone's coming.

1112
01:47:23.395 --> 01:47:25.062
Get the boys.

1113
01:47:27.482 --> 01:47:30.109
Margaret, come quickly.

1114
01:47:30.318 --> 01:47:33.112
Let's go.
Boys, come.

1115
01:47:33.697 --> 01:47:34.738
Go.

1116
01:47:39.369 --> 01:47:41.120
Stay close.

1117
01:47:46.877 --> 01:47:48.294
This way.

1118
01:48:04.769 --> 01:48:06.061
Follow me.

1119
01:48:09.441 --> 01:48:11.984
We'll go downstairs to the kitchen.

1120
01:48:18.116 --> 01:48:20.409
Margaret, quick!
Get down there! Fast!

1121
01:48:32.297 --> 01:48:34.340
Samuel, get down there fast!

1122
01:49:22.931 --> 01:49:24.848
<i>(CLICKS)</i>

1123
01:49:31.690 --> 01:49:33.691
REDCOAT 1: Beneath the sill. There.

1124
01:49:36.236 --> 01:49:37.778
There's no one in the house.

1125
01:49:37.988 --> 01:49:39.446
They can't be far.

1126
01:49:39.864 --> 01:49:42.283
Search the outbuildings
and the woods, quickly.

1127
01:50:19.988 --> 01:50:21.864
REDCOAT 2: Prepare to fire the house.

1128
01:50:22.657 --> 01:50:24.033
Go.

1129
01:50:43.762 --> 01:50:45.763
REDCOAT 3: This one's head
of the house slaves.

1130
01:50:50.935 --> 01:50:52.519
TAVINGTON: Where are they hiding?

1131
01:50:54.773 --> 01:50:55.939
<i>(GASPING)</i>

1132
01:50:56.358 --> 01:50:58.734
Keep looking!
They're here somewhere!

1133
01:51:04.574 --> 01:51:05.824
- Gabriel.
- Where's Father?

1134
01:51:05.992 --> 01:51:08.243
- Shh.
- REDCOAT 4: Torch the house!

1135
01:51:11.539 --> 01:51:13.874
<i>(WHINNYING)</i>

1136
01:51:25.887 --> 01:51:26.929
To horse!

1137
01:51:34.270 --> 01:51:35.979
Come on! It's all right.

1138
01:51:36.189 --> 01:51:38.107
Susan, come here.

1139
01:51:47.283 --> 01:51:48.492
Charlotte.

1140
01:52:04.300 --> 01:52:07.177
They won't stop looking for us.

1141
01:52:09.472 --> 01:52:11.640
You'll be safe
where we're taking you.

1142
01:52:12.475 --> 01:52:15.185
Father said it was
a perfect place to hide.

1143
01:52:17.647 --> 01:52:19.148
How is he?

1144
01:52:21.109 --> 01:52:23.026
<i>(SIGHS)</i>

1145
01:52:24.529 --> 01:52:26.196
I don't know. I'm his son.

1146
01:52:26.448 --> 01:52:28.323
Where is Father?

1147
01:52:29.868 --> 01:52:31.452
Speaking for months now.

1148
01:52:31.661 --> 01:52:33.245
Speaking for months.

1149
01:52:33.455 --> 01:52:35.080
Why did he go?

1150
01:52:35.248 --> 01:52:37.291
<i>(CLEARS THROAT)</i>

1151
01:52:37.459 --> 01:52:41.336
He didn't want those mean men
to find you, so he led them away.

1152
01:52:41.546 --> 01:52:43.922
He'll come see you
as soon as he can.

1153
01:52:44.382 --> 01:52:46.884
I don't care. I hate him.

1154
01:52:48.595 --> 01:52:50.304
Susan, you don't hate him.

1155
01:52:50.513 --> 01:52:54.016
I hate him, and I hope
he never comes back.

1156
01:53:27.842 --> 01:53:29.718
It's the children.

1157
01:53:30.762 --> 01:53:31.804
Abigale!

1158
01:53:33.681 --> 01:53:35.224
WILLIAM: You're alive!

1159
01:53:45.360 --> 01:53:49.196
I know it's not much,
but you can stay here with me.

1160
01:54:08.258 --> 01:54:10.759
It's beautiful.

1161
01:54:11.261 --> 01:54:13.011
Thank you.

1162
01:54:25.149 --> 01:54:28.986
She spoke. Susan talked to you?

1163
01:54:29.195 --> 01:54:30.863
In full sentences.

1164
01:54:31.072 --> 01:54:33.699
As if she'd been speaking all along.

1165
01:54:36.077 --> 01:54:38.036
Damn, I wasn't there for it.

1166
01:54:39.247 --> 01:54:40.372
What did she say?

1167
01:54:42.917 --> 01:54:44.710
She said...

1168
01:54:46.212 --> 01:54:49.381
that she loves you and misses you,

1169
01:54:49.757 --> 01:54:52.050
but she understands
why you can't be with her.

1170
01:54:55.430 --> 01:54:57.264
My Lord, she said that.

1171
01:54:57.932 --> 01:54:59.308
Isn't that something?

1172
01:55:03.475 --> 01:55:06.352
Tavington has a list of our men.
He's burning our homes,

1173
01:55:06.562 --> 01:55:08.437
killing whomever resists.

1174
01:55:09.064 --> 01:55:12.483
- Where?
- Seven homes along the Santee so far.

1175
01:56:00.657 --> 01:56:02.408
REVEREND: John.

1176
01:56:11.209 --> 01:56:13.544
John, this is not a time
for vengeance.

1177
01:56:14.421 --> 01:56:17.006
This is a time for mourning.

1178
01:56:21.637 --> 01:56:23.387
John.

1179
01:56:32.147 --> 01:56:33.439
No!

1180
01:56:38.987 --> 01:56:40.446
Oh... Oh...

1181
01:56:51.458 --> 01:56:53.209
Attend to your families.

1182
01:56:55.587 --> 01:56:57.880
One week furlough for all men.

1183
01:56:58.715 --> 01:57:03.010
Any man who does not return will not be
thought a coward or uncommitted.

1184
01:57:19.111 --> 01:57:21.862
Father!

1185
01:57:22.030 --> 01:57:23.572
Papa!

1186
01:57:23.782 --> 01:57:27.159
<i>(LAUGHING)</i>

1187
01:57:29.621 --> 01:57:31.789
My God, they're huge.
What have you been feeding them?

1188
01:57:31.957 --> 01:57:34.667
They're from good stock
on their father's side.

1189
01:57:34.835 --> 01:57:36.544
Thank you.

1190
01:57:43.760 --> 01:57:45.052
Susan?

1191
01:57:58.734 --> 01:58:00.901
<i>(THUNDER CRASHES)</i>

1192
01:58:25.218 --> 01:58:28.596
I see it. There it is. Look.
Look, Father.

1193
01:58:30.766 --> 01:58:32.641
NATHAN: I got it! I got it!

1194
01:58:33.018 --> 01:58:34.059
BENJAMIN: You got it.

1195
01:58:34.853 --> 01:58:36.228
I got it!

1196
01:58:36.438 --> 01:58:37.521
- Careful.
- I caught it.

1197
01:58:37.731 --> 01:58:40.357
NATHAN: All the fish are over here.
Let's get them.

1198
01:58:47.240 --> 01:58:49.116
GABRIEL: Father, what changed you?

1199
01:58:51.703 --> 01:58:53.412
Are you sure I have?

1200
01:58:53.789 --> 01:58:56.582
Yes. You changed.

1201
01:59:04.049 --> 01:59:05.424
That's simple.

1202
01:59:06.218 --> 01:59:07.259
It was your mother.

1203
01:59:12.599 --> 01:59:14.517
A woman can have a strange effect
on a man.

1204
01:59:15.185 --> 01:59:16.644
Yeah.

1205
01:59:16.812 --> 01:59:18.437
There were times...

1206
01:59:19.105 --> 01:59:21.357
I had trouble breathing
around your mother.

1207
01:59:22.567 --> 01:59:24.235
I know the feeling.

1208
01:59:26.321 --> 01:59:27.947
You once said...

1209
01:59:30.909 --> 01:59:33.452
when I had a family of my own,
that I'd understand.

1210
01:59:37.415 --> 01:59:38.958
You were right.

1211
01:59:41.545 --> 01:59:43.420
You're trying to tell me something.

1212
01:59:45.340 --> 01:59:47.341
<i>(RIDERS APPROACH)</i>

1213
02:00:00.313 --> 02:00:01.689
- Apple?
- Thank you.

1214
02:00:08.780 --> 02:00:09.905
Congratulations.

1215
02:00:10.115 --> 02:00:11.782
REVEREND: <i>Anne Patricia Howard,</i>

1216
02:00:12.075 --> 02:00:16.203
will you have this man to be
your husband to live in marriage?

1217
02:00:16.538 --> 02:00:19.123
Will you love, comfort
and honor him,

1218
02:00:19.332 --> 02:00:21.542
for so long as you both shall live?

1219
02:00:22.127 --> 02:00:23.502
I will.

1220
02:00:23.920 --> 02:00:27.131
Gabriel Edward Martin, will you have
this woman to be your wife,

1221
02:00:27.340 --> 02:00:30.009
to live together
in the covenant of marriage?

1222
02:00:30.385 --> 02:00:34.305
Will you love, comfort and honor her
as long as you both shall live?

1223
02:00:34.764 --> 02:00:35.848
I will.

1224
02:00:36.057 --> 02:00:38.893
Then by the power vested in me
by our mutual faith

1225
02:00:39.144 --> 02:00:41.020
in the Lord, our God,

1226
02:00:41.271 --> 02:00:44.565
I now pronounce you man and wife.

1227
02:01:11.718 --> 02:01:13.969
I'm sorry we didn't give you
more warning.

1228
02:01:14.179 --> 02:01:15.220
It's fine.

1229
02:01:15.805 --> 02:01:17.222
I have something for you.

1230
02:01:19.976 --> 02:01:21.727
It belonged to Gabriel's mother.

1231
02:01:21.937 --> 02:01:23.646
It's beautiful.

1232
02:01:24.648 --> 02:01:25.898
Allow me.

1233
02:01:27.233 --> 02:01:28.692
It's the North Star.

1234
02:01:29.277 --> 02:01:32.863
That's the only star in the sky
that never moves.

1235
02:01:33.281 --> 02:01:36.200
It's constant, unwavering.

1236
02:01:36.701 --> 02:01:38.035
A guide.

1237
02:01:41.623 --> 02:01:43.123
I'd be honored.

1238
02:01:48.380 --> 02:01:49.421
May I?

1239
02:01:49.631 --> 02:01:51.715
- If you must.
- I must.

1240
02:02:07.983 --> 02:02:09.483
May I sit with you?

1241
02:02:09.776 --> 02:02:11.777
It's a free country.

1242
02:02:12.487 --> 02:02:13.904
Or at least it will be.

1243
02:02:15.991 --> 02:02:17.324
<i>(SIGHS)</i>

1244
02:02:26.167 --> 02:02:28.252
I'm not my sister.

1245
02:02:29.295 --> 02:02:30.963
I know that.

1246
02:02:31.673 --> 02:02:33.132
Do you?

1247
02:02:34.426 --> 02:02:35.968
Yes, I do.

1248
02:02:37.012 --> 02:02:38.595
Very well, then.

1249
02:02:40.682 --> 02:02:42.516
<i>(SIGHS)</i>

1250
02:02:43.184 --> 02:02:44.226
Well?

1251
02:02:45.937 --> 02:02:47.229
Well what?

1252
02:02:49.149 --> 02:02:50.649
Oh.

1253
02:03:09.419 --> 02:03:11.253
I'll see you in Pembroke soon.

1254
02:03:11.463 --> 02:03:13.213
Not soon enough.

1255
02:03:13.882 --> 02:03:15.799
Nathan, I'm counting on you
to make sure--

1256
02:03:16.009 --> 02:03:17.551
- Know.
- What?

1257
02:03:17.761 --> 02:03:19.553
Say my prayers,
take care of everyone.

1258
02:03:19.721 --> 02:03:21.305
Couldn't have said it better.

1259
02:03:26.102 --> 02:03:29.021
Goodbye.

1260
02:03:49.167 --> 02:03:50.417
Goodbye, Susan.

1261
02:03:53.004 --> 02:03:54.171
Goodbye?

1262
02:03:57.300 --> 02:03:58.967
Just one word, that's all I want.

1263
02:04:01.429 --> 02:04:03.097
No?

1264
02:04:08.186 --> 02:04:09.269
All right.

1265
02:04:36.965 --> 02:04:38.382
Papa!

1266
02:04:41.052 --> 02:04:43.428
Papa, don't go! I'll say anything.

1267
02:04:48.184 --> 02:04:49.560
Please, Papa.

1268
02:04:51.980 --> 02:04:54.022
I'll say anything you want.

1269
02:04:54.232 --> 02:04:57.359
Tell me what you want me to say.
I'll say anything.

1270
02:05:00.238 --> 02:05:03.031
- I promise, Papa. Please don't go.
- Susan. Susan.

1271
02:05:04.159 --> 02:05:05.492
I promise.

1272
02:05:06.369 --> 02:05:07.828
I'll come back.

1273
02:05:08.663 --> 02:05:10.706
I'll come back. You believe me?

1274
02:05:14.127 --> 02:05:16.211
You know, you make me very happy.

1275
02:05:52.165 --> 02:05:53.916
Just the three of us?

1276
02:05:54.375 --> 02:05:56.793
John Raskin did come by earlier.

1277
02:05:57.629 --> 02:05:59.546
He looked around, then he left.

1278
02:06:00.632 --> 02:06:01.965
He would've made four.

1279
02:06:02.467 --> 02:06:04.218
Four would have been better.

1280
02:06:39.504 --> 02:06:42.881
I got another two months to go
before I get to twelve months.

1281
02:06:48.263 --> 02:06:49.304
Colonel.

1282
02:06:50.473 --> 02:06:51.765
Reverend.

1283
02:06:55.270 --> 02:06:56.728
Trust the French.

1284
02:06:57.522 --> 02:06:58.730
Yes, trust the French.

1285
02:06:58.940 --> 02:07:02.526
Where else do I get the opportunity
to kill a few Redcoats?

1286
02:07:03.069 --> 02:07:06.280
Perhaps a few wounded ones
when you are not looking.

1287
02:07:29.595 --> 02:07:30.929
Whoa.

1288
02:07:32.974 --> 02:07:35.100
Everyone must gather
at the church.

1289
02:07:35.601 --> 02:07:36.643
Mr. Wilkins?

1290
02:07:38.146 --> 02:07:41.273
Colonel Tavington wishes to address
the whole village.

1291
02:07:58.875 --> 02:08:03.003
This town has given aid
to Benjamin Martin and his rebels.

1292
02:08:03.588 --> 02:08:05.422
I wish to know his whereabouts.

1293
02:08:06.883 --> 02:08:08.216
So,

1294
02:08:08.468 --> 02:08:10.344
anyone who comes forward

1295
02:08:10.720 --> 02:08:12.888
may be forgiven their treason.

1296
02:08:18.561 --> 02:08:19.603
Very well.

1297
02:08:19.896 --> 02:08:22.314
- You had your chance.
- MAN: Wait!

1298
02:08:23.441 --> 02:08:25.650
- This man gives them supplies.
- Quiet!

1299
02:08:25.860 --> 02:08:27.819
- He brings them to Black Swamp.
- He's a liar!

1300
02:08:28.029 --> 02:08:30.113
In the marsh,
by the old Spanish mission.

1301
02:08:31.115 --> 02:08:32.282
This man here?

1302
02:08:32.700 --> 02:08:34.659
- Yes.
- The Black Swamp, you say?

1303
02:08:35.036 --> 02:08:37.037
By the old Spanish mission.

1304
02:08:39.123 --> 02:08:40.540
Thank you very much.

1305
02:08:46.714 --> 02:08:48.256
Shut the doors.

1306
02:08:50.468 --> 02:08:52.427
But you said we'd be forgiven.

1307
02:08:52.637 --> 02:08:53.887
And indeed you may!

1308
02:08:56.641 --> 02:08:58.308
That's between you and God.

1309
02:09:05.525 --> 02:09:06.900
Be strong. We must.

1310
02:09:08.861 --> 02:09:10.529
I'll fire the town on your orders.

1311
02:09:10.696 --> 02:09:12.030
The town?

1312
02:09:12.824 --> 02:09:14.366
Burn the church.

1313
02:09:16.911 --> 02:09:18.662
There's no honor in this.

1314
02:09:20.998 --> 02:09:23.792
Didn't you say all those
who stand against England

1315
02:09:24.001 --> 02:09:26.503
deserve to die a traitor's death?

1316
02:09:29.173 --> 02:09:31.883
Burn the church, captain.

1317
02:09:43.980 --> 02:09:45.021
Give me the torch.

1318
02:10:18.389 --> 02:10:20.891
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

1319
02:10:28.191 --> 02:10:30.692
The honor is found in the end,
not the means.

1320
02:10:31.986 --> 02:10:33.695
This will be forgotten.

1321
02:10:34.447 --> 02:10:35.572
Bordon.

1322
02:10:47.543 --> 02:10:50.921
<i>(SCREAMING AND CRYING)</i>

1323
02:12:15.214 --> 02:12:16.548
Anne!

1324
02:12:20.720 --> 02:12:22.345
Mrs. Howard?

1325
02:12:26.517 --> 02:12:28.268
Where is everybody?

1326
02:12:33.274 --> 02:12:35.442
They're not here.

1327
02:13:43.552 --> 02:13:45.095
Gabriel's gone.

1328
02:13:52.770 --> 02:14:01.444
Yah!

1329
02:14:30.391 --> 02:14:32.767
To arms! To arms!

1330
02:14:41.610 --> 02:14:43.653
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

1331
02:15:06.719 --> 02:15:08.762
<i>(GRUNTING)</i>

1332
02:18:37.221 --> 02:18:38.638
Yah.

1333
02:18:52.403 --> 02:18:53.695
Father.

1334
02:18:55.114 --> 02:18:57.281
Just don't talk. Don't talk.

1335
02:19:03.747 --> 02:19:04.872
Father.

1336
02:19:05.416 --> 02:19:07.583
- I'm sorry.
- Be quiet.

1337
02:19:07.793 --> 02:19:09.919
I'll take care of you.
You'll be all right.

1338
02:19:12.965 --> 02:19:16.551
I'm sorry about Thomas.

1339
02:19:22.474 --> 02:19:24.809
Oh, son, that wasn't your fault.

1340
02:19:28.897 --> 02:19:30.148
That was mine.

1341
02:19:34.528 --> 02:19:37.739
Hold on. You're gonna be all right.

1342
02:19:40.367 --> 02:19:43.286
Don't go. Gabriel, don't.

1343
02:20:00.846 --> 02:20:04.515
Oh. Oh.

1344
02:20:12.357 --> 02:20:14.650
Oh, God help me. God help me.

1345
02:20:48.727 --> 02:20:50.019
Where is he?

1346
02:20:57.986 --> 02:20:59.862
BURWELL: I'll help you bury him.

1347
02:21:02.074 --> 02:21:03.366
I'll bury him.

1348
02:21:06.620 --> 02:21:09.413
My wife in Alexandria is with child.

1349
02:21:10.874 --> 02:21:12.583
My first.

1350
02:21:13.210 --> 02:21:15.086
I fight for that child.

1351
02:21:17.756 --> 02:21:20.216
Benjamin, nothing will replace
your sons.

1352
02:21:21.552 --> 02:21:25.721
But if you come with us,
you can justify their sacrifice.

1353
02:21:27.558 --> 02:21:28.975
Why?

1354
02:21:30.727 --> 02:21:34.730
Why do men feel
they can justify death?

1355
02:21:41.321 --> 02:21:43.239
Is it arrogance or...?

1356
02:21:47.953 --> 02:21:49.912
I have long feared...

1357
02:21:51.623 --> 02:21:55.168
that my sins would return
to visit me.

1358
02:21:58.130 --> 02:22:00.756
And the cost is more
than I can bear.

1359
02:22:02.092 --> 02:22:05.928
Benjamin, we have a chance.

1360
02:22:06.471 --> 02:22:09.682
Greene and Dan Morgan
are down from Virginia.

1361
02:22:12.394 --> 02:22:15.938
If we win this next battle, victory
in the war is within our grasp.

1362
02:22:16.106 --> 02:22:17.148
Go, then.

1363
02:22:17.441 --> 02:22:19.317
Seek your victory.

1364
02:22:22.613 --> 02:22:25.698
I'm small issue to it.
You're wrong, Benjamin.

1365
02:22:26.450 --> 02:22:28.451
You matter to your men...

1366
02:22:29.953 --> 02:22:31.871
and to others as well.

1367
02:22:32.289 --> 02:22:34.081
Your victories

1368
02:22:34.291 --> 02:22:36.167
and your losses...

1369
02:22:37.461 --> 02:22:39.712
are shared by more than you know.

1370
02:22:40.797 --> 02:22:42.965
Stay with us.

1371
02:22:43.467 --> 02:22:45.384
Stay the course.

1372
02:22:55.187 --> 02:22:57.313
I have run my course.

1373
02:23:17.334 --> 02:23:19.835
You men will be leaving with us.

1374
02:23:21.380 --> 02:23:24.215
Yes. Prepare the baggage.

1375
02:24:06.091 --> 02:24:09.885
<i>(BAND PLAYS)</i>

1376
02:24:28.739 --> 02:24:29.780
Jean.

1377
02:24:42.627 --> 02:24:47.340
<i>(MEN CHEERING)</i>

1378
02:25:28.298 --> 02:25:30.424
You will be missed tomorrow, colonel.

1379
02:25:30.759 --> 02:25:33.260
- Missed, my lord?
- Your wound.

1380
02:25:34.388 --> 02:25:36.764
It's nothing, my lord.

1381
02:25:37.099 --> 02:25:40.184
I am, as ever, ready to serve.

1382
02:25:40.352 --> 02:25:42.228
Very well.

1383
02:25:42.396 --> 02:25:44.814
Make sure you do.

1384
02:25:45.357 --> 02:25:48.818
I stand on the eve of the greatest
victory of my career. Don't fail me.

1385
02:25:49.736 --> 02:25:54.532
My efforts in no small measure
have brought you here.

1386
02:25:54.699 --> 02:25:56.325
I grant you that small measure

1387
02:25:56.493 --> 02:25:59.995
in spite of your failure
to deliver the ghost to me.

1388
02:26:00.997 --> 02:26:02.623
Thus far.

1389
02:26:03.875 --> 02:26:06.919
I will not tolerate a premature charge

1390
02:26:07.087 --> 02:26:10.923
born of your eagerness for glory.

1391
02:26:11.341 --> 02:26:14.718
Wait for my order.

1392
02:26:15.095 --> 02:26:19.432
Or you may abandon any hope of Ohio.

1393
02:26:22.894 --> 02:26:26.063
BURWELL: Tomorrow's battle can alter
the course of the war.

1394
02:26:26.273 --> 02:26:29.275
General Greene, what exactly is
the task before us?

1395
02:26:29.484 --> 02:26:32.570
GREENE: Gentlemen,
Cornwallis has us cornered.

1396
02:26:33.238 --> 02:26:34.947
Not only does he outnumber us,

1397
02:26:35.157 --> 02:26:38.200
but nearly half of our force
is militia.

1398
02:26:39.536 --> 02:26:41.829
Unreliable, at best.

1399
02:26:42.164 --> 02:26:43.998
Excuse me, sir.

1400
02:26:45.709 --> 02:26:47.460
I believe you underestimate
our militia.

1401
02:26:49.671 --> 02:26:51.046
All of you do.

1402
02:26:51.840 --> 02:26:54.508
We've seen our militia lines break
time and again.

1403
02:26:54.718 --> 02:26:56.343
Kips Bay, Princeton.

1404
02:26:56.720 --> 02:26:58.804
But the British have seen that too.

1405
02:26:59.723 --> 02:27:03.476
Cornwallis' own letters bear out
that he has no respect for the militia.

1406
02:27:04.227 --> 02:27:06.604
What are you suggesting, Ben?

1407
02:27:08.023 --> 02:27:09.940
I'm suggesting we use that.

1408
02:27:17.115 --> 02:27:21.118
I know you men have sacrificed
a lot so far.

1409
02:27:21.328 --> 02:27:24.705
But all I'm asking is that you

1410
02:27:24.915 --> 02:27:28.083
let the front line of the militia
fire two shots tomorrow.

1411
02:27:30.253 --> 02:27:33.339
A lot can happen in the time it takes
to fire two shots.

1412
02:27:33.632 --> 02:27:36.091
Especially against British Regulars.

1413
02:27:37.093 --> 02:27:40.846
Indeed. That's why I'm not asking you
to fire three.

1414
02:28:12.420 --> 02:28:13.796
<i>(CLEARS THROAT)</i>

1415
02:28:37.988 --> 02:28:40.364
If I die, I will die well dressed.

1416
02:29:04.472 --> 02:29:07.850
<i>(BOOMING)</i>

1417
02:29:26.578 --> 02:29:27.703
REDCOAT 1: Fire!

1418
02:29:31.541 --> 02:29:34.418
- REDCOAT 2: Battalion!
- REDCOAT 3: Company, halt!

1419
02:29:51.519 --> 02:29:52.603
BENJAMIN: Harry,

1420
02:29:53.563 --> 02:29:55.522
will you give this to my children?

1421
02:30:06.076 --> 02:30:07.242
Thank you.

1422
02:30:16.461 --> 02:30:18.170
It's October now.

1423
02:30:20.799 --> 02:30:22.049
I know.

1424
02:30:22.967 --> 02:30:24.885
It's more than 12 months.

1425
02:30:25.345 --> 02:30:26.637
You're a free man.

1426
02:30:27.806 --> 02:30:30.599
I'm here now on my own accord.

1427
02:30:34.437 --> 02:30:36.522
I'm honored to have you with us.

1428
02:30:38.858 --> 02:30:40.109
honored.

1429
02:30:41.736 --> 02:30:44.279
VILLENEUVE: Shoulder arms!

1430
02:30:49.994 --> 02:30:51.620
Forward...

1431
02:30:52.414 --> 02:30:53.706
march!

1432
02:30:58.670 --> 02:31:00.462
How old were your daughters?

1433
02:31:02.549 --> 02:31:05.050
Violette was 12 and Pauline, 10.

1434
02:31:06.219 --> 02:31:08.178
They had green eyes.

1435
02:31:09.472 --> 02:31:11.223
I'm sure they were lovely.

1436
02:31:12.892 --> 02:31:14.685
Yes, they were.

1437
02:31:26.406 --> 02:31:27.614
- Battalion!
- REDCOAT 4: Company!

1438
02:31:27.991 --> 02:31:29.158
March!

1439
02:31:31.369 --> 02:31:32.661
REDCOAT 1: Fire!

1440
02:31:35.415 --> 02:31:36.665
CORNWALLIS: Unless I'm dreaming,

1441
02:31:37.375 --> 02:31:41.378
I believe I see militia forming
at their center.

1442
02:31:55.769 --> 02:31:58.103
Battalion, halt!

1443
02:32:16.247 --> 02:32:18.081
Dress ranks!

1444
02:32:26.883 --> 02:32:28.383
Make ready!

1445
02:32:40.104 --> 02:32:41.939
Battalion!

1446
02:32:42.148 --> 02:32:43.190
Halt!

1447
02:32:46.277 --> 02:32:47.444
Take aim!

1448
02:32:50.949 --> 02:32:51.990
- Fire!
- Fire!

1449
02:32:58.540 --> 02:32:59.915
Take aim!

1450
02:33:03.086 --> 02:33:04.169
Fire!

1451
02:33:05.630 --> 02:33:06.922
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

1452
02:33:25.191 --> 02:33:26.441
Hold the line!

1453
02:33:32.407 --> 02:33:35.659
- Prepare to charge!
- We haven't been given that order.

1454
02:33:36.035 --> 02:33:39.538
Charge!

1455
02:33:43.084 --> 02:33:44.459
Tavington.

1456
02:33:44.669 --> 02:33:46.879
Damn him! Damn that man!

1457
02:33:48.756 --> 02:33:50.257
REDCOAT 5: Make ready.

1458
02:33:50.842 --> 02:33:52.342
Take aim!

1459
02:33:53.219 --> 02:33:54.261
Fire!

1460
02:33:55.555 --> 02:33:56.889
Take aim!

1461
02:33:57.807 --> 02:33:58.849
Fire!

1462
02:33:59.017 --> 02:34:00.142
Retreat!

1463
02:34:06.190 --> 02:34:10.193
Bayonet charge. We'll see who takes
the glory from this field.

1464
02:34:10.570 --> 02:34:12.154
Charge!

1465
02:34:32.050 --> 02:34:33.425
Congratulations, my lord.

1466
02:34:33.676 --> 02:34:35.302
Infantry reserve into the center.

1467
02:34:35.511 --> 02:34:36.803
But you've taken the field.

1468
02:34:37.013 --> 02:34:38.388
Now we'll take their spirits.

1469
02:34:38.598 --> 02:34:41.642
Send the battalion over that hill
and crush them.

1470
02:34:41.851 --> 02:34:43.310
It ends today.

1471
02:35:06.584 --> 02:35:07.751
Hold the charge!

1472
02:35:08.711 --> 02:35:09.795
BURWELL: Fire!

1473
02:35:10.004 --> 02:35:12.297
Hold the charge!

1474
02:35:16.052 --> 02:35:17.427
Fire!

1475
02:35:22.976 --> 02:35:24.059
Take aim!

1476
02:35:25.728 --> 02:35:27.354
Fire!

1477
02:35:35.613 --> 02:35:37.155
Charge!

1478
02:35:43.997 --> 02:35:45.580
Charge bayonets!

1479
02:35:45.790 --> 02:35:50.752
<i>(SCREAMING AND GRUNTING)</i>

1480
02:36:14.777 --> 02:36:15.944
BURWELL: Halt!

1481
02:36:17.155 --> 02:36:18.697
Hold! Dress your ranks!

1482
02:36:21.200 --> 02:36:22.409
REDCOAT 6: Fire!

1483
02:36:25.955 --> 02:36:27.456
Charge!

1484
02:36:51.105 --> 02:36:52.773
MAN: Retreat!

1485
02:36:58.029 --> 02:36:59.112
Colonel!

1486
02:37:01.032 --> 02:37:02.449
The line is faltering!

1487
02:37:03.910 --> 02:37:06.411
Retreat! Retreat!

1488
02:37:14.295 --> 02:37:15.712
Wait!

1489
02:37:16.506 --> 02:37:18.256
No retreat!

1490
02:37:22.053 --> 02:37:28.016
Hold the line!

1491
02:37:30.103 --> 02:37:33.313
<i>(YELLING)</i>

1492
02:37:39.737 --> 02:37:42.781
Push forward, men!

1493
02:38:32.248 --> 02:38:34.541
Artillery, concentrate on the center.

1494
02:38:49.765 --> 02:38:53.476
If we reform and wheel right,
we may be able to turn their flank.

1495
02:38:53.769 --> 02:38:55.687
You dream, general.

1496
02:41:58.204 --> 02:42:00.747
Kill me before the war is over,
will you?

1497
02:42:02.416 --> 02:42:05.085
It appears you are not

1498
02:42:05.294 --> 02:42:07.504
the better man.

1499
02:42:21.185 --> 02:42:22.227
You're right.

1500
02:42:27.024 --> 02:42:29.150
My sons were better men.

1501
02:42:56.887 --> 02:42:58.346
Sound the retreat.

1502
02:43:01.892 --> 02:43:03.351
Sound...

1503
02:43:04.478 --> 02:43:05.687
retreat.

1504
02:43:23.706 --> 02:43:24.747
BENJAMIN: <i>Dear Charlotte,</i>

1505
02:43:25.499 --> 02:43:27.250
<i>The war has turned.</i>

1506
02:43:27.460 --> 02:43:30.962
<i>General Cornwallis took flight</i>
<i>with his army and moved north.</i>

1507
02:43:31.130 --> 02:43:34.340
<i>We continued to engage the British,</i>
<i>and in the following months,</i>

1508
02:43:34.508 --> 02:43:37.760
<i>Cornwallis entrenched himself</i>
<i>at Yorktown, Virginia.</i>

1509
02:43:39.388 --> 02:43:41.556
<i>Washington escaped from the north</i>

1510
02:43:41.765 --> 02:43:44.976
<i>and surrounded Cornwallis,</i>
<i>who could not retreat to the seas.</i>

1511
02:43:45.311 --> 02:43:48.521
<i>lt was blocked off by</i>
<i>our long-lost friends,</i>

1512
02:43:48.772 --> 02:43:51.232
<i>who had finally arrived.</i>

1513
02:43:55.779 --> 02:43:57.197
<i>Vive la France.</i>

1514
02:43:59.909 --> 02:44:01.493
<i>Vive la libert.</i>

1515
02:44:03.871 --> 02:44:05.038
<i>(SPEAKS FRENCH)</i>

1516
02:44:13.672 --> 02:44:15.548
My lord, I beseech you.

1517
02:44:16.175 --> 02:44:18.426
You must order the surrender.

1518
02:44:19.261 --> 02:44:22.472
CORNWALLIS: How could it come to this?
An army of rabble.

1519
02:44:23.098 --> 02:44:24.516
Peasants.

1520
02:44:26.685 --> 02:44:28.645
Everything will change.

1521
02:44:32.149 --> 02:44:34.150
Everything has changed.

1522
02:44:34.944 --> 02:44:36.986
BENJAMIN: <i>Though he eventually surrendered,</i>

1523
02:44:37.196 --> 02:44:39.656
<i>Cornwallis himself hid in shame,</i>

1524
02:44:39.865 --> 02:44:43.451
<i>appointing his subordinate</i>
<i>to relinquish his sword.</i>

1525
02:44:44.662 --> 02:44:47.789
<i>With the war ending,</i>
<i>and our militia disbanding,</i>

1526
02:44:47.998 --> 02:44:50.667
<i>l take measure of what</i>
<i>we have lost</i>

1527
02:44:50.876 --> 02:44:52.418
<i>and what we have won.</i>

1528
02:44:53.587 --> 02:44:58.299
<i>My hope and prayer is that</i>
<i>the sacrifices borne by so many</i>

1529
02:44:58.551 --> 02:45:02.387
<i>will spawn and fulfil the promise</i>
<i>of our new nation.</i>

1530
02:45:03.806 --> 02:45:07.725
<i>Tell the children, and especially Susan,</i>
<i>that I will keep my promise,</i>

1531
02:45:07.935 --> 02:45:11.563
<i>as I will be returning</i>
<i>to you all soon.</i>

1532
02:45:17.695 --> 02:45:19.362
Where will you go now?

1533
02:45:20.114 --> 02:45:22.365
Home. Start over.

1534
